SECTION 26. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 11, Part 1, is amended
deleting the part and substituting:
63-11-101. Chapter definitions.
As used in this chapter:
(1) "Board" means the board of examiners in psychology, created by §
63-11-102;
(2) "Commissioner" means the commissioner of health;
(3) "Department" means the department of health; and
(4) "Division" means the division of health related boards in the
department of health, created by § 63-1-101.
63-11-102. Creation – Membership – Immunity.
(a) There is created a board of examiners in psychology to consist of ten (10)
members, nine (9) of whom are appointed by the governor under conditions set forth in
subsection (b).
(b)
- 8 - 017271

(1) Two (2) members must be chosen from, and be members of the
faculty with the rank of assistant professor or above of, the accredited colleges
and universities in the state and be engaged in teaching, research, or
administration of psychology.
(2) Four (4) members must be licensed psychologists.
(3) One (1) member must be a private citizen who is neither a licensed
psychologist nor a licensed psychological examiner or licensed senior
psychological examiner and who has no professional or commercial interest in
the practice of psychology.
(4) Two (2) members must be either a licensed psychological examiner
or a licensed senior psychological examiner.
(c) The chair of the applied behavior analyst licensing committee of the board of
examiners in psychology shall serve as an ex officio voting member of the board.
(d) The board shall perform such duties and exercise such powers as this
chapter prescribes and confers upon it.
(e) Members of the board are not liable to civil actions for any act performed in
good faith in the performance of their duties as set forth in this chapter.
63-11-103. Appointments – Vacancies.
(a) All appointments are for terms of five (5) years.
(b) Vacancies must be filled for any unexpired terms, and members shall serve
until their successors are appointed and have been qualified. Only practicing
psychologists must be appointed to succeed practicing psychologists, and only
academic psychologists must be appointed to succeed academic psychologists. Board
members are ineligible for reappointments for a period of five (5) years following
completion of their terms.
(c)
- 9 - 017271

(1) Appointments to the board for the psychologist members may be
made from lists of qualified candidates to be furnished to the governor by
interested psychology groups, including, but not limited to, the Tennessee
Psychological Association. Each list must contain the names of academic
psychologists and practicing psychologists. All vacancies occurring in the board
may be filled by the governor for the unexpired term from the lists of qualified
candidates within thirty (30) days after the vacancy occurs. The governor shall
consult with such interested groups to determine qualified persons to fill positions
on the board.
(2) In making appointments to the board, the governor shall strive to
ensure that at least one (1) person serving on the board is sixty (60) years of age
or older.
63-11-104. Oath of office – Records.
(a) Immediately and before entering upon the duties of the office, the members
of the board shall take the constitutional oath of office and file the same in the office of
the governor.
(b) The board shall have available for the governor adequate records of its
proceedings and of all licenses and certificates.
63-11-105. Organization – Administration.
(a) The board shall elect annually a chair and vice chair.
(b) Each member must receive all necessary expenses incident to conducting
the business of the board and, in addition thereto, be entitled to a per diem of one
hundred dollars ($100) for each day's service in conducting the business of the board.
All reimbursements for travel expenses must be in accordance with the comprehensive
travel regulations as promulgated by the department of finance and administration and
approved by the attorney general and reporter.
- 10 - 017271

(c) The board shall hold at least one (1) regular meeting each year. Called
meetings may be held at the discretion of the chair or at the written request of two (2)
members of the board.
(d) The board shall adopt a seal, which must be affixed to all certificates issued
by the board.
(e) Five (5) members of the board at all times constitute a quorum. An action
taken by the board requires the majority of the quorum present.
(f) The board is empowered to hire such assistance as is necessary to carry on
its activities, within the limits of funds available to the board, and is empowered to accept
grants from foundations or institutions to develop tests and carry out its functions.
(g) The board shall receive administrative support from the division.
(h) The board shall establish continuing educational requirements for all licenses
created in this chapter.
63-11-106. Powers and duties.
(a) The board has the following powers and duties in addition to the powers and
duties granted to or imposed upon it by this chapter:
(1) To prescribe rules for examination of candidates for a license created
by this chapter;
(2) To ascertain the qualifications and fitness of applicants for all licenses
created by this chapter;
(3) To issue licenses to applicants who successfully meet the
qualifications for licensure under this chapter and the board's rules;
(4) To receive complaints and review issues related to complaints and
disciplinary actions involving a person licensed under this chapter;
(5) To conduct investigations, as appropriate, into allegations against
licensees of the board;
(6) To issue private letter rulings in accordance with § 63-1-174;
- 11 - 017271

(7) To make rules and establish fees as are necessary to carry out and
make effective this chapter; and
(8) To administer oaths, summon witnesses, and take testimony in all
matters relating to the board's duties.
(b) All rules promulgated by the board must comply with the Uniform
Administrative Procedures Act, compiled in title 4, chapter 5.
(c) The board shall use the division-employed investigators, inspectors, and
agents, or use any other means necessary, to bring about and maintain the rigid
administration and enforcement of this chapter and all laws regulating the practice of a
profession created by this chapter.
63-11-107. License – Application.
(a) Applicants for a license created by this chapter shall submit an application on
the form created by the board and any required fees to the division.
(b) In addition to the specific requirements for licensure in this chapter, the
application must include evidence that the applicant meets the following requirements:
(1) The applicant is of good moral character and conducts the applicant's
professional activities in accordance with the accepted professional and ethical
standards;
(2) The applicant has not had a professional credential refused, revoked,
suspended, or restricted and does not have a complaint, allegation, or
investigation pending in any regulatory jurisdiction in the United States or in
another country for unprofessional conduct, and has not committed an act that
would constitute grounds for discipline of a license under § 63-11-109; and
(3) The applicant is either a United States citizen or a qualified alien, as
defined in § 4-58-102.
(c) The division and applicant shall comply with the criminal background
requirements of § 63-1-116.
- 12 - 017271

(d) Each applicant seeking licensure must pay all fees as set by the board,
including, but not limited to, nonrefundable application fees and examination fees.
(e) All licensees must comply with § 63-1-109.
(f) Portions of an application involving an applicant's health condition, including
mental health conditions and substance use disorders, and records involving an
applicant's health condition, are confidential, privileged, and not public records subject to
inspection by citizens of this state, as described in § 10-7-503.
(g)
(1) When the board receives a completed application for initial licensure,
or a completed application for licensure, from an applicant who is licensed in
another state or territory of the United States or in the District of Columbia, then
the board shall, within sixty (60) days from the date the board receives the
completed application:
(A) Render a decision on the application; or
(B) Inform the applicant of the need to appear before the board.
(2) As used in this subsection (g), "completed application" means an
application that satisfies all statutory and board rule requirements.
63-11-108. License renewal – Retirement.
(a) A license issued under this chapter is valid for twenty-four (24) months from
the date of issuance and is renewable biennially at the end of the birth month of the
licensee. The division, with the approval of the commissioner, shall establish a system
of license or certification renewals at alternative intervals that allow for the distribution of
the license or certification workload as uniformly as is practicable throughout the
calendar year. Licenses or certificates issued under the alternative method are valid for
twenty-four (24) months and expire on the last day of the last month of the license or
certification period.
- 13 - 017271

(b) In addition to any requirements of this chapter creating the license, a
licensee requesting renewal of a certificate must provide the following to the division in
advance of the expiration date of the license:
(1) A completed application on a form provided by the division and
payment of the fees set by the board; and
(2) A certified or sworn statement that the licensee:
(A) Has completed all the continuing education hours required for
the licensee, whether required by statute or rule, prior to the expiration
date of the license; and
(B) Has not had a professional credential revoked, suspended, or
restricted by a certification board, and does not have a complaint,
allegation, or investigation pending in this state or in any regulatory
jurisdiction for unethical or unprofessional conduct.
(c) If a licensee fails to pay the license renewal fee within sixty (60) days after it
becomes due, as provided in this section, the licensee must apply for a new license
rather than renew the existing license.
(d) A licensee who has lost the ability to renew pursuant to subsection (c) may
make application in writing to the board for the reinstatement of the license, and, upon
good cause shown, the board, in its discretion, may reinstate the license upon payment
of all past due renewal fees and upon further payment of a sum set by the board.
(e) Applicants and licensees shall notify the board of the following within thirty
(30) days of their occurrence:
(1) A change of name, address, or other vital information;
(2) The filing of a criminal charge or civil action against the applicant or
licensee;
- 14 - 017271

(3) The initiation of disciplinary charges, investigations, findings, or
sanctions by a healthcare organization, federal or state agency, or other
professional association against the applicant or licensee; and
(4) Any other change in information provided by the applicant or licensee
to the division.
(f) A person licensed or certified to practice by this chapter who has retired or
may retire on or after the effective date of this act from such practice in this state must
not be made to register as required by this chapter if the person files with this board an
affidavit on a form to be furnished by the board, which affidavit must state the date on
which the person retired from such practice and such other facts as tend to verify the
retirement as the board deems necessary. If the person thereafter reengages in such
practice in this state, then the person must apply for registration with the board as
provided by this chapter and meet other requirements as may be set by the board.
(g) For the purpose of effecting service of process upon a licensee, the board
may notify the licensee by certified mail, return receipt requested, at the address on file
with the division.
63-11-109. License denial, suspension, or revocation – Disciplinary grounds –
Hearing.
(a) The board has the power:
(1) To deny an application for a license to an applicant who applies for
the same through reciprocity or otherwise;
(2) To permanently or temporarily withhold issuance of a license;
(3) To issue a license contingent upon such circumstances or
requirements as the board may determine;
(4) To issue a conditional license that is limited or restricted for such time
and in such manner as the board may determine, including a limited license of
temporary duration for applicants out of practice for an extended period of time;
- 15 - 017271

(5) To issue discipline to an applicant or licensee, or on a previously
issued license, including, but not limited to, private censures and warnings, public
reprimands, limits, restrictions, conditions, or suspension periods, for such time
and in such manner as the board may deem proper in its discretion;
(6) To discipline a licensee who has been disciplined by another state of
the United States for any acts or omissions that would constitute grounds for
discipline if licensed in this state, following the procedure in § 63-1-120; or
(7) To revoke, or permanently revoke, a license.
(b) The grounds upon which the board may exercise the powers enumerated in
subsection (a) include, but are not limited to:
(1) Engaging in unprofessional, dishonorable, or unethical conduct;
(2) Making false statements or representations, being guilty of fraud or
deceit in obtaining admission to practice, or being guilty of fraud or deceit in the
course of professional practice;
(3) Violating or attempting to violate, directly or indirectly, or assisting in
or abetting the violation of, or conspiring to violate, a criminal statute of this state,
this chapter, a rule promulgated by the board, or a lawful order of the board
issued pursuant to rules;
(4) Engaging in gross professional liability, or a pattern of continued or
repeated professional liability, ignorance, negligence, or incompetence, in the
course of practice;
(5) Being habitually intoxicated or personally misusing drugs, or using
intoxicating liquors, narcotics, controlled substances, controlled substance
analogues, or other drugs or stimulants, in such manner as to adversely affect
the person's ability to safely practice in the profession;
(6) Willfully betraying a professional secret;
- 16 - 017271

(7) Advertising the professional practice with untrue or misleading
statements or causing the publication or circulation of fraudulent advertising
relative to any disease, human ailment, or condition;
(8) Willfully violating the rules that may be promulgated by the board to
regulate advertising by practitioners who are under the jurisdiction of the board;
(9) Being convicted of a felony, an offense under state or federal laws
relative to drugs or the professional practice, an offense involving moral
turpitude, or an offense for which the licensee or applicant is required to register
as a sexual offender or violent sexual offender pursuant to the Tennessee Sexual
Offender and Violent Sexual Offender Registration, Verification and Tracking Act
of 2004, compiled in title 40, chapter 39, part 2;
(10) Engaging in professional practice when mentally or physically
unable to safely do so;
(11) Making or signing in one's professional capacity a certificate that is
known to be false at the time one makes or signs the certificate;
(12) Offering, undertaking, or agreeing to cure or treat a disease, injury,
ailment, or infirmity by a secret means, method, device, or instrumentality;
(13) Giving, receiving, or aiding or abetting in the giving or receiving of
rebates, either directly or indirectly;
(14) Engaging in practice under a false or assumed name or the
impersonation of another practitioner of a like, similar, or different name;
(15) Practicing a level of psychology inappropriate or beyond the scope
of the particular license or licenses or certification held by the licensee or certified
person; and
(16) Engaging in any other action deemed to be grounds for disciplinary
action under rules promulgated by the board.
- 17 - 017271

(c) All proceedings for disciplinary action against a licensee under this chapter
must be conducted in accordance with the Uniform Administrative Procedures Act,
compiled in title 4, chapter 5.
(d) An action taken under this section is subject to the applicable provisions of
the Fresh Start Act, compiled in chapter 1, part 1 of this title.
SECTION 27. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 11, Part 2, is amended by
deleting the part and substituting:
63-11-201. Levels of psychological practice.
(a) Five (5) levels of psychological practice are defined for the purposes of this
chapter. Such levels are to be known and referred to as:
(1) Psychological examiner;
(2) Senior psychological examiner;
(3) Psychologist;
(4) Certified psychological assistant; and
(5) Certified psychological testing technician.
(b) An individual who engages in the practice of psychology as a psychological
examiner, senior psychological examiner, or psychologist must possess a valid license
under this chapter.
(c) A person engaged in the practice of psychology as a certified psychological
assistant or certified psychological testing technician must possess a valid certificate to
practice under this chapter.
(d)
(1) This section does not prohibit a charitable clinic from employing or
contracting with a psychologist if the contractual relationship between the
psychologist and the charitable clinic is evidenced by a written contract, job
description, or documentation, containing language that does not restrict the
- 18 - 017271

psychologist from exercising independent professional judgment in diagnosing
and treating patients.
(2) As used in this subsection (d), "charitable clinic" means an entity that
meets the following standards:
(A) Has received a determination of exemption from the internal
revenue service under 26 U.S.C. § 501(c)(3) or is a distinct part of an
entity that has received such a determination of exemption;
(B) Has clinical facilities located in this state;
(C) Has a primary mission to provide health care or dental care
services to low-income, uninsured, or underserved individuals;
(D) Provides one (1) or more of the following services for free or
at a discounted rate:
(i) Medical care;
(ii) Dental care;
(iii) Mental health care; or
(iv) Prescription medications;
(E) Utilizes volunteer healthcare professionals and nonclinical
volunteers; and
(F) Is not required to be licensed under § 68-11-202(a)(1).
63-11-202. Practice of a psychological examiner.
(a) A person practices as a psychological examiner within the meaning of this
chapter when the person claims to be a psychological examiner or renders to individuals
or to the public health-related clinical activities or services involving the application of
recognized principles, methods, and procedures of the science and profession of
psychology, such as interviewing or administering and interpreting tests of mental
abilities, aptitudes, interests, and personality characteristics, for such purposes as
psychological evaluation or for educational or vocational selection, guidance, or
- 19 - 017271

placement. The psychological examiner shall practice the following health-related
clinical activities or services only under qualified supervision provided by a psychologist
or a senior psychological examiner:
(1) Overall personality appraisal or classification;
(2) Personality counseling;
(3) Psychotherapy;
(4) Behavior analysis; or
(5) Personality readjustment techniques.
(b) This section does not expand or restrict the scope of practice for a
psychological examiner.
(c) Those psychological examiners rendering health-related clinical activities or
services who have been duly licensed prior to July 1, 1991, who request to the board in
writing or via online application, are senior psychological examiners. Those duly
licensed psychological examiners rendering health-related clinical activities or services
licensed after July 1, 1991, qualify for senior psychological examiner licensure upon
completion of at least five (5) years of applied experience from the date their temporary
permit was first issued by the board and upon completion of two hundred (200) hours of
post-licensure continuing education units distributed by categories, according to the
November 1997 rules governing continuing education units. A person practices as a
senior psychological examiner within the meaning of this chapter when the person
claims to be a senior psychological examiner or renders to individuals or to the public for
remuneration a service involving the application of recognized principles, methods, and
procedures of the science and profession of psychology. A senior psychological
examiner, while possessing a different scope of practice than a psychologist, is
considered a health service provider and able to engage in the following designated
areas of health-related psychological practice without supervision:
- 20 - 017271

(1) Interviewing or administering and interpreting tests of mental abilities,
aptitudes, interests, and personality characteristics for such purposes as
psychological evaluation or for educational or vocational selection, guidance, or
placement;
(2) Overall personality appraisal or classification, psychological testing,
projective testing, and evaluations for disability or vocational purposes;
(3) Diagnosis of nervous and mental disorders;
(4) Personality counseling;
(5) Psychotherapy;
(6) Behavior analysis;
(7) Personality readjustment techniques; or
(8) Supervision of a psychological examiner.
63-11-203. Practice of a psychologist.
(a) As used in this part, "practice of psychology":
(1) Means, without regard to whether payment is received for services
rendered, the observation, description, evaluation, interpretation, and
modification of human behavior by the application of psychological principles,
methods, and procedures for the purpose of assessing, preventing, or eliminating
symptomatic, maladaptive, or undesired behavior and of enhancing interpersonal
relationships, work and life adjustment, personal effectiveness, behavioral health,
and mental health of individuals, families, groups, and the public; and
(2) Includes:
(A) Psychological testing and the evaluation or assessment of
personal characteristics, such as intelligence, personality, abilities,
interests, aptitudes, and neuropsychological functioning;
(B) Counseling, psychoanalysis, psychotherapy, hypnosis,
biofeedback, and behavior analysis and therapy;
- 21 - 017271

(C) Psychological diagnosis and treatment of mental, emotional,
and nervous disorders or disabilities; alcoholism and substance abuse;
disorders of habit or conduct; and psychological aspects of physical
illness, accident, injury, or disability;
(D) Case management and utilization review of psychological
services;
(E) Psychoeducational evaluation, therapy, remediation, and
consultation;
(F) Forensic evaluation; provided, that a person licensed under
this chapter performing forensic evaluation is considered to be acting
within their lawful scope of practice and the practice of forensic evaluation
is not exclusive to individuals licensed under this chapter;
(G) Parent coordination; provided, that a person licensed under
this chapter performing parent coordination is considered to be acting
within their lawful scope of practice and the practice of parent
coordination is not exclusive to individuals licensed under this chapter;
and
(H) Telepsychology, which means the practice of psychology via
electronic communications technology by a person licensed under this
chapter.
(b) A person represents to be a psychologist if that person uses a title or
description of services incorporating the words "psychology," "psychological," or
"psychologist," if the person possesses expert qualification in any area of psychology or
if that person offers to the public or renders to individuals or to groups of individuals
services pursuant to the practice of psychology.
63-11-204. Psychotherapy limitations – Conduct outside psychological practice
prohibited.
- 22 - 017271

(a) Sections 63-11-201 — 63-11-203 do not permit the use of those forms of
psychotherapy that involve the administration or prescription of drugs or electroshock or
in any way infringe upon the practice of medicine as defined in the laws of this state.
(b) A psychologist, psychological examiner, senior psychological examiner,
certified psychological assistant, or certified psychological testing technician who
engages in psychotherapy shall establish and maintain effective intercommunication with
a psychologically oriented physician, usually a psychiatrist, to make provision for the
diagnosis and treatment of medical problems by a physician with an unlimited license to
practice the healing arts in this state.
(c) A psychologist, psychological examiner, senior psychological examiner,
certified psychological assistant, or certified psychological testing technician shall not
attempt to diagnose, prescribe for, treat, or advise a client with reference to problems or
complaints falling outside the boundaries of psychological practice.
(d) Sections 63-11-203 and 63-11-208(c) and (d) are subject to the limitations of
this section.
63-11-205. Use of titles.
(a)
(1) Individuals and organizations shall not present themselves, or be
presented, to the public by a title incorporating the name "psychological,"
"psychologist," or "psychology" other than those licensed as psychologists,
psychological examiners, senior psychological examiners, certified psychological
assistants, or certified psychological testing technicians.
(2) A psychological scientist employed by a recognized research
laboratory, college, or university may use the academic or research title
conferred upon the psychological scientist by the administration of the laboratory,
college, or university.
- 23 - 017271

(3) Persons licensed by the state board of education in areas of school
psychology, school psychologist, or school psychological services worker and
employed as such in the department of education or in a public or nonpublic
elementary or secondary school are not required to be licensed under this part
while performing in the course of their employment. This chapter does not apply
to persons licensed by the state board of education in areas of school
psychology, school psychologist, or school psychological services worker who
are employed as such in the department of education or in a public or nonpublic
elementary or secondary school while performing in the course of their
employment.
(b) This section does not permit such persons to offer their services to any other
persons or organizations as consultants or to accept remuneration for psychological
services other than that of their institutional salaries unless they have been licensed or
certified under this chapter.
(c) Visiting lecturers from recognized laboratories, colleges, or universities are
exempt from this section and may utilize their academic or research title when
presenting lectures to similar institutions or organizations.
(d) Students of psychology, psychological interns, and other persons preparing
for the profession of psychological examiner, senior psychological examiner, certified
psychological assistant, certified psychological testing technician, or psychologist under
qualified supervision in recognized training institutions or facilities may be designated by
such titles as "psychological intern," "psychological trainee," or others clearly indicating
such training status.
(e) Psychologists with competency in areas other than the provision of health
services retain the right to use the title of "licensed psychologist" with competence in
areas other than health services and to practice within their area of competency.
63-11-206. Unauthorized practice – Exemptions – Temporary licenses.
- 24 - 017271

(a) A person who engages in the practice of psychology and does not then
possess in full force and virtue a valid license to practice as a psychological examiner,
psychologist, or senior psychological examiner, or a valid certificate to practice as a
psychological assistant or psychological testing technician, under this chapter commits a
Class B misdemeanor.
(b) This chapter does not prevent members of other recognized professions who
are licensed, certified, or regulated under the laws of this state from rendering services
consistent with their professional training and code of ethics as long as they do not
represent themselves to be psychologists, psychological examiners, senior
psychological examiners, certified psychological assistants, or certified psychological
testing technicians. Duly recognized members of the clergy are not restricted from
functioning in their ministerial capacity as long as they do not represent themselves to be
psychologists, psychological examiners, senior psychological examiners, certified
psychological assistants, or certified psychological testing technicians.
(c)
(1) Students of psychology, psychological interns, and other persons
preparing for the profession of psychological examiner, psychologist, senior
psychological examiner, certified psychological assistant, or certified
psychological testing technician may perform as a part of their training the
functions in §§ 63-11-202 and 63-11-203, but only under qualified supervision.
(2) A person practices as a certified psychological assistant within the
meaning of this chapter when the person claims to be a certified psychological
assistant or renders to individuals or to the public for remuneration a service
involving the application of recognized principles, methods, and procedures of
the science and profession of psychology and only under the direct employment
and supervision of either the psychologist or senior psychological examiner
employing the certified psychological assistant or the employing community
- 25 - 017271

mental health center or state governmental agency. All work performed by a
certified psychological assistant must be supervised by a psychologist or senior
psychological examiner as determined by the board.
(3) A person practices as a certified psychological testing technician
within the meaning of this chapter when the person claims to be a certified
psychological testing technician or renders to individuals or the public for
remuneration a service involving the application of recognized principles,
methods, and procedures of the science and profession of psychology and only
under the supervision of either the psychologist or senior psychological examiner
employing the certified psychological testing technician or the employing
community mental health center or state governmental agency. All work
performed by a certified psychological testing technician must be supervised by a
psychologist or senior psychological examiner as determined by the board.
(d) Use of psychological techniques by governmental institutions and by
business and industrial organizations for employment placement, evaluation, promotion,
or job adjustment of their own officers or employees or by employment agencies for the
evaluation of their own clients prior to recommendation for employment is also
specifically allowed; however, an industrial or business firm or corporation shall not sell
or offer to the public or to other firms or corporations for remuneration psychological
services as specified in §§ 63-11-202 and 63-11-203, unless the services are performed
or supervised by individuals duly and appropriately licensed under this chapter.
(e)
(1)
(A)
(i) The board may issue a temporary license to an
applicant who has successfully completed the academic course
- 26 - 017271

work and training for the license sought, and who has not yet
taken the required written examinations.
(ii) A temporary license is valid for a period not to exceed
one (1) year. The board may extend the expiration date of a
temporary license following a petition from the licensee and
finding that extraordinary circumstances exist that necessitate a
delay in taking a required written examination prior to the
expiration of the initial temporary license period.
(iii) A temporary license is revoked thirty (30) days after
the date a temporary licensee receives notice of the licensee's
second failure of the examination for professional practice in
psychology (EPPP) or jurisprudence examination. During the
thirty-day period prior to revocation of the temporary license, the
licensee and the licensee's supervisor shall ensure the notification
and transfer of care for the temporary licensee's clients.
(B) The temporary license allows the applicant to perform the
functions specified in §§ 63-11-202 and 63-11-203, for which the
applicant is seeking licensure under qualified supervision.
(C) In order to receive a temporary license, the applicant must
submit a completed application for a temporary license with the
applicant's completed application for the desired license and all
appropriate fees to the board.
(2)
(A)
(i) A temporary license may be issued by the board for an
applicant who has a current license from another state or territory.
The temporary license allows the applicant to perform under
- 27 - 017271

qualified supervision the functions specified in §§ 63-11-202 and
63-11-203.
(ii) In order to receive a temporary license, the applicant
must submit a completed application for a temporary license with
the applicant's completed application for the desired license and
all appropriate fees to the board.
(iii) Applications for temporary licenses for applicants
currently licensed in another state or territory must be reviewed
and approved or denied by a current member of the board
designated by the board to perform this function.
(iv) If an applicant is issued a temporary license, then the
license remains valid until the board grants or denies the license
application.
(v) However, a person must not be issued more than one
(1) temporary license, and a temporary license must not be valid
for a period of more than one (1) year.
(B) Such a temporary license may be issued to allow an applicant
to perform the functions specified in § 63-11-203 if the applicant has:
(i) Successfully completed an approved American
Psychological Association academic course of study;
(ii) Previously taken and passed, according to this state's
standards, the national licensing examination; and
(iii) A current license in another state or territory in good
standing.
(C) Such a temporary license with designation as a health service
provider may be issued to an applicant who meets the requirements of
subdivision (e)(2)(B) and has:
- 28 - 017271

(i) Successfully completed an American Psychological
Association-approved internship; and
(ii) Had at least one (1) year of full-time postdoctoral
experience delivering health services.
(D) Such a temporary license may be issued to allow an applicant
to perform the functions specified in § 63-11-202 if the applicant has:
(i) Previously taken and passed, according to Tennessee
standards, the national licensing examination; and
(ii) A current license in another state or territory in good
standing.
(3) The board shall set the fee for all temporary licenses in an amount
not to exceed one hundred dollars ($100). Until such time as the board
establishes a fee by rule, the fee is fifty dollars ($50.00).
(f) This chapter does not expand or limit, in any way, the practice of
psychological examiners as provided in § 63-11-202, senior psychological examiners as
provided in § 63-11-202, or certified psychological assistants as provided in subdivision
(c)(2) and § 63-11-207(b), and does not limit the use of the title "psychological examiner"
for persons duly licensed as psychological examiners.
(g) Notwithstanding subsection (a), persons providing services in programs of
the department of mental health and substance abuse services or the department of
disability and aging either as employees or through contract agencies are not engaged
in the practice of psychology and need not be licensed or certified under this chapter
unless such persons provide services as a psychological examiner, psychologist, senior
psychological examiner, certified psychological assistant, or certified psychological
testing technician.
(h)
- 29 - 017271

(1) A provisional license to practice as a psychologist with the
designation as a health service provider may be issued by the board of
examiners in psychology to an applicant who has successfully completed the
academic and internship requirements of § 63-11-208(c)(1) and (d)(1) and who is
to be engaged in a one-year postdoctoral experience required by § 63-11-
208(d)(2)(A). The provisional licensure allows the applicant to perform the
functions specified in §§ 63-11-203 and 63-11-208(d)(2)(B) under the qualified
supervision of a psychologist acceptable to the board and who is licensed in this
state with a designation as a health service provider in good standing.
(2) In order for a provisional license to remain valid, the licensee must
take and pass the examination for professional practice in psychology (EPPP) at
the level set for licensure as a psychologist in this state within one (1) year of the
issuance of the provisional license unless the applicant previously passed the
EPPP at that level. A provisional license is revoked thirty (30) days after the date
a provisional licensee receives notice of the licensee's second failure of the
EPPP following issuance of the provisional license. During the thirty-day period
prior to revocation of the provisional license, the licensee and the licensee's
supervisor shall ensure the notification and transfer of care for the provisional
licensee's clients.
(3) In order for the provisional license to remain valid, the licensee must
take and pass the oral or jurisprudence examination, or both, developed by the
board within two (2) years of the issuance of the provisional license. A
provisional license is revoked thirty (30) days after the date a provisional licensee
receives notice of the licensee's second failure of the oral or jurisprudence
examination following issuance of the provisional license. During the thirty-day
period prior to revocation of the provisional license, the licensee and the
- 30 - 017271

licensee's supervisor shall ensure the notification and transfer of care for the
provisional licensee's clients.
(4) The board may consider petitions of the licensee regarding
extraordinary circumstances that would necessitate delay in taking the written or
oral examination.
63-11-207. License for psychological examiner, certified psychological assistant,
and certified psychological testing technician.
(a) The board shall not issue new psychological examiner licenses. The
discontinued issuance of psychological examiner licenses or the designation of senior
psychological examiners in no way impairs or abridges the right of duly licensed
psychological examiners to practice within the scope of their license or to renew their
licensure status as required by law. Unless the person has obtained a license to
practice as a psychological examiner or senior psychological examiner, as issued by the
board, it is unlawful for the person to practice. A person violates this chapter if the
person practices as a certified psychological testing technician without first having
obtained a proper certificate.
(b)
(1) A person seeking to practice as a certified psychological assistant in
this state shall, before it is lawful for the person to practice as a certified
psychological assistant, make application to the board, upon such form and in
such manner as is adopted and prescribed by the board, including, but not
limited to, the proper registration with the board of the supervisor of record for the
certified psychological assistant. Unless the person obtains a proper certificate
as issued by the board, it is unlawful for a person to practice, and if the person
practices as a certified psychological assistant without first having obtained a
proper certificate, then the person has violated this chapter.
- 31 - 017271

(2) In addition to the requirements of § 63-11-107, a candidate for
certification shall furnish the board with satisfactory evidence that the candidate:
(A) Is not considered by the board to be engaged in unethical
practice; and
(B) Has had two (2) academic years of graduate training in
psychology, including a master's degree, from an accredited educational
institution recognized by the board as maintaining satisfactory standards,
or in lieu thereof, such training and experience as the board considers
equivalent thereto. Such graduate training must include specialized
training in psychological assessment, test construction and measurement,
the administration and interpretation of psychological testing, interviewing
skills, and social history methods. The board may, at its discretion,
consider equivalent training and experience when presented by qualified
applicants with a master's degree in psychology whose credentials differ
slightly than those prescribed in this subdivision (b)(2)(B). However, all
applicants must in their graduate training show evidence of supervised
practicum experience in the administration and interpretation of
psychological testing, assessment procedures, and social history and
feedback interviewing techniques as determined by the board in order to
fulfill educational requirements for certification.
(c)
(1) A person seeking to practice as a certified psychological testing
technician in this state shall, before it is lawful for the person to practice as a
certified psychological testing technician, make application to the board, upon
such form and in such manner as is adopted and prescribed by the board,
including, but not limited to, the proper registration with the board of the
supervisor or supervisors of record for the certified psychological testing
- 32 - 017271

technician. Unless the person obtains a proper certificate as issued by the
board, it is unlawful for the person to practice. A person violates this chapter if
the person practices as a certified psychological testing technician without first
having obtained a proper certificate.
(2) As used in subdivision (c)(1), "practice as a certified psychological
testing technician" means the individual is duly authorized by the board to
administer and score standardized psychological and neuropsychological tests
and to observe and describe a client's test behavior and test responses. A
certified psychological testing technician shall not select psychological or
neuropsychological tests or versions of tests to be given, interpret test results,
write test results, or give test feedback to clients.
(3) The services provided by a certified psychological testing technician
must be provided under the supervision of a psychologist or senior psychological
examiner who is registered with the board as a supervisor of record to provide
such supervision for the certified psychological testing technician. The certified
psychological testing technician must be employed by, or contracted with, the
same work setting as the supervising psychologist or senior psychological
examiner who is registered with the board.
(4) In addition to the requirements of § 63-11-107, a candidate for
certification shall furnish the board with satisfactory evidence that the candidate:
(A) Is not considered by the board to be engaged in unethical
practice; and
(B) Proof of completion of a bachelor's degree or graduate
degree, or proof of current enrollment in a graduate degree program, from
a regionally accredited university, college, or professional school, in either
psychology or education with a specialization in educational psychology,
counseling psychology, or school psychology. The candidate's
- 33 - 017271

educational training must consist of a minimum of seventy-two (72) hours
of total education and training relating to psychological or
neuropsychological test administration and scoring that includes the
following:
(i) At least twenty (20) hours of direct observation,
including at least ten (10) hours of direct observation of a licensed
psychologist or senior psychological examiner administering and
scoring tests, and at least ten (10) hours of direct observation of
either a licensed psychologist, senior psychological examiner, or
certified psychological testing technician duly registered by the
board administering and scoring tests;
(ii) At least forty (40) hours of administering and scoring
tests in the presence of a licensed psychologist or senior
psychological examiner; and
(iii) At least twelve (12) hours of additional education on
topics related to best practices for the functions identified in
subdivision (c)(2). Of those twelve (12) hours, at least three (3)
hours must be specifically dedicated to law and ethics, and at
least three (3) hours must be dedicated to multicultural
competency. Additional topics must relate to growth, knowledge,
and skill-based training that would enhance the candidate's
professional skill in providing care for persons with medical,
psychiatric, neurocognitive, and developmental conditions
commonly assessed by psychologists and neuropsychologists.
(5) The education and training specified in subdivisions (c)(4)(B)(i)-(iii)
may be obtained through any combination of the following:
- 34 - 017271

(A) Participating in individual or group instruction by a licensed
psychologist or senior psychological examiner;
(B) Engaging in independent learning directed by a licensed
psychologist or senior psychological examiner;
(C) Completing graduate-level coursework at a regionally
accredited university, college, or professional school; or
(D) Taking continuing education courses from organizations
offering continuing education sponsorships.
(6) This chapter does not prevent a person engaged in gaining the
experience, training, or education required by subdivision (c)(4)(B) from
administering and scoring psychological and neuropsychological tests.
63-11-208. License for psychologist.
(a) A person wishing to obtain the right to practice as a psychologist in this state,
who has not been licensed on or before the effective date of this act, shall, before it is
lawful for the person to practice psychology in this state, make application to the board
through the chair upon such form and in such manner as is adopted and prescribed by
the board.
(b) Unless the person has obtained a license as prescribed in subsection (a), it
is unlawful for the person to practice, and if the person practices psychology without first
having obtained such a license, then the person has violated this chapter.
(c)
(1) In addition to the requirements of § 63-11-107, a candidate for such
license shall furnish the board with satisfactory evidence that the candidate:
(A) Has received a doctorate in psychology from an accredited
educational institution recognized by the board as maintaining satisfactory
standards. After December 31, 1995, all such doctoral programs must be
approved by the American Psychological Association and listed by the
- 35 - 017271

American Association of State Psychology Boards, or meet equivalent
standards as are determined by the board;
(B) Is competent in psychology, as shown by passing such
examinations, written or oral, or both, as the board deems necessary;
(C) Is not considered by the board to be engaged in unethical
practice; and
(D) Has not within the preceding six (6) months failed an
examination given by the board.
(2) The board may, at its discretion, consider equivalent training and
experience when presented by qualified applicants with a doctoral degree in
psychology whose credentials differ slightly than those prescribed in subdivisions
(c)(1)(A) and (d)(2)(A). In such cases, the applicant must petition the board for a
waiver and specifically request the board utilize its discretionary authority.
(d) A licensed psychologist who provides or offers health services to the public
must be designated by the board as a health service provider. In addition to the
requirements for licensure as a psychologist prescribed in subsection (c), an applicant
for designation as a health service provider must demonstrate to the board that the
applicant:
(1) Has had at least a one-year internship at a site where health services
are normally provided and that is part of an organized integrated training
program. After December 30, 1995, all such internships must be approved by
the American Psychological Association (APA) or listed by the Association of
Psychological Post-Doctoral and Internship Centers (APPIC), or meet equivalent
standards as are determined by the board; and
(2)
(A) Has successfully completed at least one (1) year postdoctoral
experience delivering health services, supervised by a licensed
- 36 - 017271

psychologist designated by the board as a health service provider. If the
one (1) year of postdoctoral experience was not in this state, then
equivalent supervision must be documented to the satisfaction of the
board; and
(B) For purposes of this chapter, "health service," in any variation,
means the delivery of direct, preventive, assessment, and therapeutic
intervention services to individuals whose growth, adjustment, or
functioning is actually impaired or may be at risk of impairment.
(e) Notwithstanding subsection (d), the board may designate as a health service
provider, with practice restriction to recipients in an intellectual disabilities' facility under
the department of disability and aging, a person who meets all of the following criteria:
(1) The person holds a doctorate in psychology from a regionally
accredited institution;
(2) The person is currently licensed as a psychologist in at least one (1)
state;
(3) The person has academic training in intellectual disability and
postdoctoral clinical experience in the field of intellectual disability of at least five
(5) years' duration;
(4) The department submits to the board a description of the applicant's
proposed functioning at the intellectual disability facility;
(5) The department certifies that:
(A) The applicant has training and experience adequate to
perform the applicant's proposed functioning within the department;
(B) The department is unable to recruit otherwise qualified
psychologists to provide psychological services; and
- 37 - 017271

(C) This inability threatens the integrity of the department's
services and the ability of the department to meet the needs of its clients;
and
(6) A psychologist granted designation as a health service provider by
the board under this subsection (e) shall surrender this designation upon
termination of the person's employment with the department, which designation
is, thereafter, null and void.
(f)
(1) Notwithstanding subsection (d), the board may designate as a health
service provider, a person who has held a valid license or certificate in another
state to practice psychology for at least ten (10) years within the last fifteen (15)
years preceding the date of application and whose previous license or
certification:
(A) Required training that is generally equivalent to the following
licensing standards in this chapter:
(i) A doctoral degree in psychology;
(ii) One (1) year of internship in an organized integrated
training program at a site delivering health services; and
(iii) One (1) year of postdoctoral training delivering health
services;
(B) Has never been the subject of disciplinary action; and
(C) Allowed the licensee to engage in practice as a health service
provider in psychology in the other state.
(2) In order to effectuate the purposes of subdivision (f)(1), the board
may promulgate emergency rules pursuant to § 4-5-208(a)(5). The rules must be
promulgated in accordance with the Uniform Administrative Procedures Act,
compiled in title 4, chapter 5.
- 38 - 017271

63-11-209. Examination of applicants for a license or certificate to practice
psychology.
(a) Examination of applicants for a license or certificate to practice psychology
may be made by the board at least once a year according to methods and in such
subject fields as may be deemed by the board to be the most practical and expeditious
to test the applicant's qualifications. Alternatively, the board may accept a nationally
recognized test.
(b)
(1) Such examinations must include the basic psychological sciences.
(2) The board shall require the examinations to be written or oral, or both;
provided, that in any written examination, the applicant is designated by a
number instead of the applicant's name so that the applicant's identity is not
disclosed to the members of the board until the examination papers have been
graded.
(3) The board shall grade the written examinations returned by the
candidates and keep them for at least one (1) year.
(4) A candidate is held to have passed the examination upon the
affirmative vote of three (3) or more members of the board.
(5) An unsuccessful candidate may, upon written request to the board,
see the candidate's graded paper.
63-11-210. Certification without examination.
(a) The board may, at its discretion, grant a certificate without an assembled
examination to a person residing or employed in the state who has not previously failed
the appropriate examination given by the board and who, at the time of application, is
licensed or certified by a similar board of another state whose standards, in the opinion
of the board, are not lower than those required by this chapter, or who has been
practicing psychology in another state and has qualifications not lower than those
- 39 - 017271

required by this chapter, and is able to satisfy to the board that to grant that person a
license would be in the public interest, or who has been certified by the American Board
of Examiners in Professional Psychology.
(b)
(1) Notwithstanding subsection (a), the board shall grant a license
without an assembled written or oral examination to a person who at the time of
application:
(A) Is licensed or certified in good standing with a similar board of
another state;
(B) Has passed the National Examination for the Practice of
Professional Psychology at a level greater than or equal to the level
required in this state;
(C) Can show reasonable proof that the applicant has available
employment in this state by means of letters or other reasonable proof;
and
(D) Received a psychologist license after January 1, 1995, but
before June 1, 1995.
(2) The board may permit a psychologist licensed in good standing in
another state, who meets standards acceptable to the board, to perform the
functions of §§ 63-11-203 and 63-11-208(d)(2)(B) and practice as a psychologist
in this state without possessing a current license for a period of time, not to
exceed twelve (12) days per year, for such purposes as special training or
consultation, special evaluation, or intervention or serving as an expert witness.
(c) This section does not permit the regular, repetitive, or ongoing provision of
psychological services, the supervision of psychological services, or the solicitation or
advertisement of services to the general public, all of which are governed by the usual
and customary processes of licensure for psychologists.
- 40 - 017271

63-11-211. Confidential relations and privileged communications.
For the purpose of this chapter, the confidential relations and communications
between licensed psychologist, licensed psychological examiner, licensed senior
psychological examiner, certified psychological assistant, or certified psychological
testing technician and client are placed upon the same basis as those provided by law
between attorney and client. This chapter does not require such privileged
communication to be disclosed.
63-11-212. Code of ethics.
The board of examiners shall, by rule, adopt a code of ethics to govern
appropriate practices or behavior as referred to in §§ 63-11-109, 63-11-207, and 63-11-
208.
63-11-213. Peer review – Immunity.
(a) As used in this section, "peer review committee" or "committee" means a
committee, board, commission, or other entity constituted by a statewide psychological
association or local psychological association for the purpose of receiving and evaluating
professional acts of other practitioners of psychology as defined in this chapter.
(b) A practitioner of psychology who serves on a peer review committee or on
any other committee is immune from liability with respect to an action taken in good faith
and without malice as a member of such committee, board, commission, or other entity.
(c) Practitioners of psychology, individuals appointed to a committee as defined
in subsection (a), and members of the boards of directors of facilities, as described in §
68-11-201, are immune from liability to a client, patient, individual, or organization for
furnishing information, data, reports, or records to any such committee or for damages
resulting from decisions, opinions, actions, or proceedings rendered, entered, or acted
upon by such committee, undertaken or performed within the scope or functions of the
duties of such committee, if made or taken in good faith and without malice and on the
basis of facts reasonably known or reasonably believed to exist.
- 41 - 017271

(d)
(1) All information, interviews, reports, statements, memoranda, or other
data furnished to a peer review committee, associational board, or governing
board, and any findings, conclusions, or recommendations resulting from the
proceedings of such committees, associational boards, and governing boards are
privileged.
(2) The records and proceedings are confidential and must be used only
in the exercise of the proper functions of the committees, associational boards, or
governing boards and not become public records nor be available for court
subpoena or discovery proceedings.
(3) This subsection (d) does not apply to records, documents, or
information otherwise available from original sources, and such records,
documents, or information are not immune from discovery or use in civil
proceedings solely due to presentation to the committee.
63-11-214. Internships.
A person currently enrolled in an internship program satisfying the requirements
of § 63-11-208(d)(1) and who completes the internship and all other degree
requirements by December 31, 1992, must be designated as a health service provider
without completing the one-year full-time supervised postdoctoral experience as
provided in § 63-11-208(d)(2) if an application for such designation is submitted by July
1, 1993.
63-11-215. Health service provider designation – Criteria.
(a) For purposes of licensure renewal, a psychologist licensed under this chapter
as a school, clinical, or counseling psychologist who was designated by the board as a
health service provider by July 1, 1993, must continue to be renewed by the board with a
designation of health service provider as long as the psychologist meets all other
requirements for a renewal license.
- 42 - 017271

(b) A psychologist licensed under this chapter other than as a school, clinical, or
counseling psychologist who was designated by the board as a health service provider
by July 1, 1993, must continue to be renewed by the board with a designation of health
service provider as long as the psychologist meets all other requirements for licensure
renewal.
63-11-216. Definitions for federal legislation and regulations and this code.
For purposes of federal legislation and regulations referencing qualifications with
respect to the provision of psychological services and other titles in this code, unless the
context otherwise requires, "licensed clinical psychologist," "licensed counseling
psychologist," or "licensed school psychologist," in any variation, refers to a psychologist
licensed under this chapter and designated as a health service provider.
63-11-217. Third-party reimbursement.
Community mental health centers, as defined in § 33-1-101; institutes or
governmental agencies; doctoral clinical psychology students in university-operated
training clinics; and those qualifying psychologists employing psychologists with
temporary or provisional licenses are eligible to receive third-party reimbursement from a
managed care plan or third-party payor for usual and customary professional services
rendered by the employed psychologist with a provisional or temporary license.
63-11-218. Medical practitioners in free health clinics – Special volunteer license.
A psychologist licensed pursuant to this chapter under a special volunteer license
who is a medical practitioner, as defined by § 63-1-201, engaged in practice at a free
health clinic is not subject to license fees under this chapter. The board of examiners in
psychology may issue a special volunteer license, as such license is defined in § 63-1-
201, to qualified applicants without fee or charge. Such license is for a period of two (2)
years and may be renewed on a biennial basis.
63-11-219. Notification of departure from community mental health center –
Patient records.
- 43 - 017271

Psychologists, senior psychological examiners, and psychological examiners are
not required to notify patients who were treated by them at community mental health
centers, as defined in § 33-1-101, of their departure from such community mental health
centers. Patient records must remain with the community mental health centers. The
transfer of patients' records must be in compliance with standards set by state and
federal law.
SECTION 28. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 11, is amended by
deleting parts 4 and 6.
SECTION 29. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 14, is amended by
deleting the chapter.
SECTION 30. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 17, is amended by
deleting part 2 and substituting:
63-17-201. Part definitions.
As used in this part, unless the context otherwise requires:
(1) "Apprentice licensee applicant" means a person who is registered
with the board, who is engaged in an approved licensing program, who is
sponsored by a hearing instrument specialist duly licensed in this state, and who
meets the qualifications of § 63-17-207;
(2) "Apprentice program" means sixty (60) classroom hours of prescribed
coursework under the direct supervision of a hearing instrument specialist, with
such coursework pertaining to all aspects of hearing instrument dispensing;
(3) "Board" means the board of communication disorders and sciences
created by § 63-17-104;
(4) "Cerumen" means a wax-like secretion from glands in the external
auditory canal;
(5) "Commissioner" means the commissioner of health;
- 44 - 017271

(6) "Division" means the division of health related boards in the
department of health;
(7) "Hearing instrument" means an instrument or device designed for or
represented as aiding, improving, or correcting defective human hearing and any
parts, attachments, or accessories of such an instrument or device;
(8) "Licensed hearing instrument specialist" means a person licensed by
this part who has passed a board-approved psychometrically sound examination
for hearing instrument specialists;
(9) "Otolaryngologist" means a physician specialist dedicated to the care
of patients with disorders of the ears, nose, throat, and related structures of the
head and neck, commonly referred to as ENTs;
(10) "Practice of dispensing and fitting hearing instruments" includes:
(A) The evaluation or measurement of the powers or range of
human hearing by means of an audiometer for the consequent selection
or adaptation for sale of hearing instruments intended to compensate for
hearing loss, and the appropriate instructions, consultations, suggestions,
recommendations, or opinions related to this practice;
(B) Making an impression of the ear, or an ear mold; and
(C) Cerumen management in the course of examining ears by a
person who holds a certification of completion of a cerumen management
course, as described in § 63-17-222; and
(11) "Sell" or "sale" includes a transfer of title or of the right to use by
lease, bailment, or any other contract, either oral or written, except wholesale
sales to distributors or dispensers.
63-17-202. Powers of the board.
In addition to the powers granted to the board in this chapter, the board shall:
- 45 - 017271

(1) Supervise and administer qualifying examinations to test the
knowledge and proficiency of applicants for a license under this part;
(2) License persons who apply to the board under this part and who are
qualified to practice the fitting of hearing instruments;
(3) Purchase and maintain or rent audiometric equipment and facilities
necessary to carry out the examination of applicants for license under this part;
(4) Issue and renew licenses under this part;
(5) Deny, suspend, or revoke licenses pursuant to this part;
(6) Appoint representatives to conduct or supervise the examination of
applicants for license under this part;
(7) Designate the time and place for examining applicants for license
under this part;
(8) Make and publish rules not inconsistent with the laws of this state that
are necessary to carry out this part;
(9) Require an annual calibration of audiometric equipment;
(10) Provide all examinations required by this part or contract with
organizations to conduct examinations;
(11) Establish minimum requirements of test procedure and test
equipment to be used in the fitting of hearing instruments and also the retention
of records of all fittings;
(12) Inspect the facilities or records, or both, of persons who practice the
fitting and selling of hearing instruments, upon a showing of probable cause of a
violation of this part;
(13) Require lists, set standards, and approve programs for trainees as
provided in § 63-17-206;
(14) Promulgate rules requiring continuing education as a prerequisite for
renewal of licenses to practice under this part; and
- 46 - 017271

(15) Employ a consultant to assist the board in its duties under this part.
63-17-203. Prohibited practice – Display of license.
(a) A person shall not engage in the sale of or practice of dispensing and fitting
hearing instruments or display a sign or, in any other way, advertise or hold out to be a
hearing instrument specialist unless direct hands-on testing and follow-up services are
provided to persons to whom the hearing instrument specialist has dispensed or sold a
hearing instrument, and such person holds a current, unsuspended, unrevoked license
issued by the board as provided in this part.
(b) The license required by this section must be kept conspicuously posted in
the specialist's principal office or place of business at all times.
63-17-204. Exemptions.
(a) This part does not prevent a person who is a physician licensed to practice
by the board of medical examiners from treating or fitting hearing instruments to the
human ear.
(b) It is lawful for a person, who meets the requirements of §§ 63-17-203 and 63-
17-205 and who is listed as an apprentice licensee applicant with the board and who is
under the direct supervision of a sponsoring licensed hearing instrument specialist, to
engage in the practice of dispensing and fitting hearing instruments if the person does so
under the direct supervision of the licensed hearing instrument specialist and with the
licensed dispenser making final selection and fitting to the client. A licensed dispenser
shall not supervise more than two (2) such apprentice licensee applicants or apprentice
licensees combined at the same time.
(c) This part does not prevent a person who is an audiologist licensed by the
board from practicing audiology, as defined in § 63-17-103, or prevent a person who is a
speech-language pathologist licensed by the board from practicing speech-language
pathology, as defined in § 63-17-103.
63-17-205. Applicant requirements.
- 47 - 017271

(a) An applicant for a license must:
(1) Be at least eighteen (18) years of age; and
(2) Have an education equivalent to two (2) years of accredited college
level coursework or national board for certification in hearing instrument sciences
(NBC-HIS) board certification.
(b) Such applicant shall pay a nonrefundable application fee as set by the board
no later than forty-five (45) days in advance of the next scheduled examination.
63-17-206. Apprentice license.
(a) Applicants who meet the requirements of § 63-17-205 with respect to age
and education may apply for an apprentice license.
(b) The apprentice licensee functions under the direct supervision of the
sponsoring licensed hearing instrument specialist for a period of at least three (3)
months after submitting an application, and during such three-month period, the
sponsoring licensed dispenser shall make the final selection and fitting of the hearing
instrument.
(c) During the apprentice period, the apprentice licensee shall complete sixty
(60) classroom hours of prescribed coursework.
(d) The apprentice license remains in effect no longer than one (1) year and
cannot be renewed.
(e) Applicants for an apprentice license shall pay the board a nonrefundable fee
as set by the board by rule.
63-17-207. Examination.
(a) Upon the payment of an examination fee as set by the board, an applicant for
a license who is notified by the board that the applicant has fulfilled the requirements of
§ 63-17-205 shall appear at a time and place, and before such persons, as the board
may designate to be examined by written and practical tests in order to demonstrate that
the applicant is qualified to practice the fitting of hearing instruments.
- 48 - 017271

(b) The board shall give at least one (1) examination of the type prescribed in
this section each year and such additional examinations as the volume of applications
may make appropriate.
63-17-208. Examination requirements.
(a) The examination described in § 63-17-207 must consist of:
(1) Tests of knowledge in the following areas as they pertain to the fitting
of hearing instruments:
(A) Basic physics of sound;
(B) The human hearing mechanism, including the science of
hearing and the causes and rehabilitation of abnormal hearing and
hearing disorders; and
(C) Structure and function of hearing instruments;
(2) Tests of proficiency in the following techniques as they pertain to the
fitting of hearing instruments:
(A) Pure tone audiometry, including air conduction testing and
bone conduction testing;
(B) Live voice or recorded voice speech audiometry, including
speech reception threshold testing and speech discrimination testing;
(C) Effective masking;
(D) Recording and evaluation of audiograms and speech
audiometry to determine hearing instrument candidacy;
(E) Selection and adaption of hearing instruments and testing of
hearing instruments;
(F) Taking earmold impressions; and
(G) Other skills as may be required for the fitting of hearing
instruments; and
(3) Tests of knowledge of this part.
- 49 - 017271

(b) The tests under this section do not include questions requiring a medical or
surgical education.
63-17-209. License fee – License without examination.
(a) Upon payment of an initial license fee as determined by the board, the board
shall issue a license to each applicant who passes the examination. An initial license
expires as provided by rules promulgated by the board.
(b) The board may, in its discretion, license as a hearing instrument specialist,
without examination, on the payment of a fee as set by the board, an applicant who is a
hearing instrument specialist, certified, registered, or licensed under the laws of another
state or country, if the applicant's qualifications for certification, registration, or licensure
meet the licensure requirements in force in this state upon the date of the specialist's
application for certification, registration, or licensure in this state.
63-17-210. Notification by licensee of changes.
Each licensee shall notify the board of a change of address of the licensee's
place of business within thirty (30) days of such change. Failure to give notice is
deemed just cause for disciplinary action by the board.
63-17-211. Registry of licensees.
The board shall issue all licenses approved by the board and maintain a registry
of all license holders. It is the duty of the board to review and approve the qualifications
of applicants for certification or renewal as hearing instrument specialists.
63-17-212. Fees – Renewals.
(a)
(1) Each licensed hearing instrument specialist shall pay to the board a
biennial renewal fee as set by the board, payable in advance, for the ensuing two
(2) years.
- 50 - 017271

(2) The board shall notify each licensee that such renewal is due. The
failure of the licensee to receive such notice does not excuse the licensee's
obligation to renew every two (2) years.
(b) When a licensed hearing instrument specialist fails to pay the license fee
within sixty (60) days after it becomes due, as provided in this section, the license of the
person is automatically revoked at the expiration of the sixty (60) days after the renewal
fee was required, without further notice or hearing.
(c) A person whose license is automatically revoked as provided in § 63-1-
107(c) may make application in writing to the council for the reinstatement of such
license, and, upon good cause being shown, the council, in its discretion, may reinstate
such license upon payment of all past due renewal fees and upon further payment of a
sum set by the council.
(d) A person licensed to practice by this part who has retired or may retire from
such practice in this state on or after the effective date of this act is not required to
register as provided by this part if the person files with the board an affidavit on a form to
be furnished by the board, which affidavit states the date on which the person retired
from such practice and such other facts as tend to verify the retirement as the board
deems necessary. If the person thereafter reengages in such practice in this state, then
the person must apply for registration with the board as provided by this part and meet
other requirements as may be set by the board.
(e)
(1) Notwithstanding this part to the contrary, the division, with the
approval of the commissioner, shall establish a system of license renewals at
alternative intervals that allow for the distribution of the license workload as
uniformly as is practicable throughout the calendar year. Licenses issued under
the alternative method are valid for twenty-four (24) months and expire on the
last day of the last month of the license period. However, during a transition
- 51 - 017271

period, or at any time thereafter when the board determines that the volume of
work for any given interval is unduly burdensome or costly, either the licenses or
renewals, or both of them, may be issued for terms of not less than six (6)
months nor more than eighteen (18) months. The fee imposed for a license
under the alternative interval method for a period of other than twenty-four (24)
months must be proportionate to the annual fee and modified in no other manner,
except that the proportional fee must be rounded off to the nearest twenty-five
cents (25¢).
(2) A renewal application must not be accepted after the last day of the
month following the license expiration date under the alternative method
authorized in this subsection (e).
63-17-213. Fees relative to the practice of dispensing hearing instruments – Use
of funds.
The board shall set the fees relating to the practice of dispensing hearing
instruments in an amount sufficient to pay all of the expenses of the board that are
directly attributable to the performance of its duties pursuant to this chapter.
Expenditures of the board for investigations and disciplinary actions against licensees of
this part are the financial responsibility of the licensees who are regulated by this
chapter. The division may maintain the existing separate accounts established for the
board and former council for licensing hearing instrument specialists if the division
combines the revenue collected such that the two (2) accounts may offset expenditures
for the board. Funds remaining in these accounts at the end of any fiscal year do not
revert to the general fund but remain available for expenditure in accordance with law.
63-17-214. Sales of hearing instruments.
(a) A person who engages in the practice of dispensing and fitting hearing
instruments shall deliver to each person supplied with a hearing instrument, by the
- 52 - 017271

dispensing person's or at the dispensing person's order or direction, a bill of sale that
contains each of the following:
(1) The signature of the licensed hearing instrument specialist, the
address of the specialist's regular place of business, and the specialist's license
number and license expiration date;
(2) The make and model of the hearing instrument supplied, and the
amount charged for the hearing instrument and whether the hearing instrument is
new, used, or rebuilt;
(3) A clear statement of the terms of sale, including the provisions
required by § 63-17-215; and
(4) The name and address of the board and a statement that the board
will receive complaints on any matter relating to the fitting and dispensing of
hearing instruments.
(b) The sale of a hearing instrument is subject to the same conditions and
provisions as are prescribed by the United States food and drug administration and the
federal trade commission.
(c) A hearing aid that is sold, fitted, or dispensed to a consumer in this state
must be clearly and permanently marked with:
(1) The name of the manufacturer or distributor or the model's name or
number;
(2) The serial number; and
(3) The year of manufacture.
63-17-215. Returns.
(a) Within thirty (30) days of the date of delivery, a purchaser of a hearing
instrument from a licensee is entitled to return the hearing instrument for any reason if
such instrument is returned in satisfactory condition and such purchaser pays only
- 53 - 017271

reasonable charges for the hearing instrument and related services. Such return
privileges apply only to a first-time purchaser of a hearing instrument.
(b) Charges to be imposed upon return of a hearing instrument as provided in
subsection (a) must be clearly stated in the bill of sale.
(c) This section does not supersede any duly promulgated regulation issued by
the federal trade commission.
63-17-216. Sponsor liability.
A person sponsoring an apprentice licensee or apprentice licensee applicant
under this part is held responsible for the acts or omissions of the sponsor's apprentice
licensee or apprentice licensee applicant within the course and scope of the licensee's or
applicant's employment, during the apprenticeship, as well as the sponsor's employees.
63-17-217. License denial, revocation, or suspension.
(a) Subject to the due process requirements of the Uniform Administrative
Procedures Act, compiled in title 4, chapter 5, a person registered under this part may
have such license denied, revoked, or suspended for a fixed period to be determined by
the board for the following causes:
(1) Having a conviction of an offense involving moral turpitude. The
record of such conviction or certified copy thereof from the clerk of the court
where the conviction occurred or by the judge of such court is sufficient evidence
to warrant revocation or suspension;
(2) Securing a license under this part through fraud or deceit;
(3) Engaging in unethical conduct or gross or repeated acts of ignorance
or inefficiency in the conduct of the person's practice;
(4) Knowingly practicing while suffering with a contagious or infectious
disease;
(5) Using a false name or alias in the practice of the profession; and
(6) Violating this part or the board's rules or orders.
- 54 - 017271

(b)
(1) The board shall promulgate rules governing the assessment of costs
against a licensee or other person found by the board to have violated this
chapter. The costs assessed by the board may include only those costs directly
related to the prosecution of the charges against the licensee or other person,
including investigatory costs where appropriate. The board shall determine the
appropriate amount of costs, if any, to be assessed in a contested case. These
costs must be reasonable and proportionate in light of the violation committed by
the licensee or other person.
(2)
(A) An elected officer of the board or a duly appointed or elected
chair has the authority to administer oaths to witnesses. Upon probable
cause being established, the board, by a vote of two-thirds (2/3) of the
total membership of the board, may issue subpoenas for the attendance
of witnesses and the production of documents and records.
(B) Service of a subpoena issued by the board must be made by
the sheriff of the county of residence of the licensee or person upon
whom the subpoena is served.
(C)
(i) A licensee or person served by subpoena has thirty
(30) days to request in writing a hearing before the board for the
sole purpose of making a special appearance to quash or modify
the subpoena. The subpoena for attendance of the person or the
production of documents and records is stayed until the board
votes upon the request to quash or modify the subpoena. A
majority vote of the total membership of the board is required to
quash or modify a subpoena.
- 55 - 017271

(ii) A motion to appeal from a decision by the board
regarding a request to quash or modify a subpoena must be made
to the chancery court in Davidson County within fifteen (15) days
of such decision.
(D) If a witness fails or refuses to obey a subpoena issued by it,
the board may make application to any court of record in this state within
the jurisdiction of which the witness is found or resides, and the court has
power to attach the body of the witness and compel the witness to appear
before the board and give testimony or produce books, records, or papers
as ordered, and any failure to obey the court order may be punished by
the court issuing the order as a civil contempt.
(E) Each witness who appears before the board by order of the
board must receive for attendance the compensation provided by law for
attendance of witnesses in a court of record, which must be paid from the
funds of the board in the same manner as all other expenses of the board
are paid.
63-17-218. Violations – Injunctions.
(a) A violation of this part is a Class B misdemeanor.
(b) The board may seek to enforce this part by petitioning a court of appropriate
jurisdiction for an injunction to enjoin continuing violations of this part or by any other
appropriate proceeding.
63-17-219. Persons licensed or in training up to July 1, 1995.
(a) A person who was a trainee or apprentice, or who had entered into a training
program to become a licensed hearing aid dispenser, by July 1, 1995, is eligible to
receive a license as a hearing instrument specialist if the person complies with the
requirements of [former] chapter 15 of this title [repealed], as it existed on July 1, 1995.
- 56 - 017271

(b) A person who was a licensed hearing aid dispenser on July 1, 1995, is
eligible to receive a license as a hearing instrument specialist. A person who was a
licensed hearing aid dispenser on July 1, 1995, who wishes to obtain a license as a
hearing instrument specialist shall submit a request to the board to receive the
appropriate license as a hearing instrument specialist. An additional fee shall not be
imposed upon persons for the issuance of a license as a hearing instrument specialist
pursuant to this subsection (b).
63-17-220. Cerumen management principles.
A licensed hearing instrument specialist shall comply with the following cerumen
management principles:
(1) The indications for cerumen management for a licensed hearing
instrument specialist include:
(A) Enabling audiometric testing;
(B) Making ear impressions;
(C) Fitting hearing protection or prosthetic devices; and
(D) Monitoring continuous use of hearing aids;
(2) The licensed hearing instrument specialist shall refer a patient who
exhibits any of the following contraindications to cerumen removal for medical
consultation or medical intervention to an otolaryngologist or a licensed
physician:
(A) An age less than twelve (12) years of age;
(B) A perforated tympanic membrane;
(C) History of pain, active drainage, or bleeding from the ear;
(D) Evidence of congenital or traumatic deformity of the ear;
(E) Ear surgery within the last six (6) months;
(F) Tympanostomy tubes, such that irrigation should not be used;
(G) A bleeding disorder;
- 57 - 017271

(H) Actual or suspected foreign body in the ear;
(I) Stenosis or bony exostosis of the ear canal;
(J) Cerumen impaction that totally occludes the ear canal;
(K) Cerumen located medial to the cartilaginous external auditory
canal; or
(L) A tympanic membrane that the licensee is unable to see;
(3) In performing cerumen removal, a licensed hearing instrument
specialist shall only remove cerumen lateral to the external auditory canal using
the following instruments:
(A) Cerumen loop;
(B) Cerumenolytic liquid;
(C) Irrigation, for patients with intact tympanic membranes and a
closed mastoid cavity, no tympanostomy tubes, no recent ear surgery,
and no recent dizziness; or
(D) Suction used lateral to the bony canal, only for patients with
no recent surgery, intact tympanic membranes, and no clear otorrhea;
(4) If the patient, while undergoing cerumen management that did not
present contraindications, complains of significant pain, exhibits uncontrolled
bleeding or a laceration of the external auditory canal, or notices the acute onset
of dizziness or vertigo or sudden hearing loss, then the licensed hearing
instrument specialist must immediately stop the procedure and refer the patient
to an otolaryngologist or a licensed physician;
(5) The licensed hearing instrument specialist shall maintain the following
proper infection control practices:
(A) Universal health precautions;
(B) Decontamination;
- 58 - 017271

(C) Cleaning, disinfection, and sterilization of multiple use
equipment; and
(D) Universal precautions for prevention of the transmission of
human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), hepatitis B virus, and other
bloodborne pathogens, as defined by occupational safety and health
standards promulgated pursuant to 29 CFR 1910;
(6) The licensed hearing instrument specialist who performs cerumen
management shall maintain a case history for every patient and informed
consent signed by the patient as part of the patient's records;
(7) The licensed hearing instrument specialist shall carry appropriate
professional liability insurance before performing cerumen removal; and
(8) The licensed hearing instrument specialist shall not require patients to
sign any form that eliminates liability if the patient is harmed.
63-17-221. Cerumen management course required – Rules.
(a) A licensed hearing instrument specialist who engages in cerumen
management, pursuant to § 63-17-221, must have completed a cerumen management
course approved by the International Hearing Society, the American Academy of
Otolaryngology-Head and Neck Surgery, or another organization approved by the board.
The course must:
(1) Be overseen by a physician, preferably an otolaryngologist;
(2) Consist of at least six (6) hours of a participant practicing removing
cerumen from an ear canal model using a variety of safe techniques; and
(3) Result in a certificate of completion and attestation of competence
signed by the overseeing physician.
(b) The board may promulgate rules to effectuate the requirements of the course
outlined in this section only after consultation with the board of medical examiners,
- 59 - 017271

established by § 63-6-101. The rules must be promulgated in accordance with the
Uniform Administrative Procedures Act, compiled in title 4, chapter 5.
63-17-222. Transfer of rules, licensing and regulatory authority, to the board of
communications disorders and sciences.
(a) The secretary of state shall transfer all rules promulgated by the [former]
council for licensing hearing instrument specialists [repealed] and in effect on the
effective date of this act to the board of communications disorders and sciences.
(b) Pursuant to the transfer of rules under subsection (a), the board of
communications disorders and sciences is authorized to regulate hearing instrument
specialists, including applying and enforcing the rules promulgated by the [former]
council for licensing hearing instrument specialists, upon the effective date of this act.
SECTION 31. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 18, is amended by
deleting the chapter.
SECTION 32. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 24, is amended by
deleting the chapter.
SECTION 33. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, is amended by deleting chapters
26, 27, 28, 30, and 31.
SECTION 34. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 63-32-102(b), is amended by
deleting the subsection and substituting:
(b) As used in this chapter, "provider" or "healthcare provider" means:
(1) A physician, regulated pursuant to chapter 6 of this title;
(2) An osteopathic physician, regulated pursuant to chapter 9 of this title;
(3) A chiropractor, regulated pursuant to chapter 4 of this title;
(4) A dentist, regulated pursuant to chapter 5 of this title;
(5) A podiatrist, regulated pursuant to chapter 3 of this title;
(6) An optometrist, regulated pursuant to chapter 8 of this title;
(7) A dietitian or nutritionist, regulated pursuant to chapter 25 of this title;
- 60 - 017271

(8) A physician assistant, regulated pursuant to chapter 19 of this title;
(9) A respiratory care practitioner, regulated pursuant to chapter 33, part
9 of this title;
(10) A pharmacist, regulated pursuant to chapter 10 of this title;
(11) An audiologist and speech pathology therapist, regulated pursuant
to chapter 17 of this title;
(12) A certified nurse practitioner, as such nurses are regulated pursuant
to § 63-7-123;
(13) A registered nurse anesthetist, regulated pursuant to chapter 7 of
this title;
(14) A social worker, regulated pursuant to chapter 23 of this title;
(15) A psychologist, regulated pursuant to chapter 11 of this title;
(16) A professional counselor, marital and family therapist, and clinical
pastoral therapist, regulated pursuant to chapter 22 of this title;
(17) A massage therapist, regulated pursuant to chapter 33, part 2 of this
title;
(18) Medical laboratory personnel, regulated pursuant to title 68, chapter
29;
(19) Alcohol and drug abuse counselors, regulated pursuant to title 68,
chapter 24;
(20) Occupational therapists and physical therapists regulated pursuant
to chapter 13 of this title;
(21) A veterinarian, regulated by chapter 12 of this title; and
(22) A nursing home administrator, regulated pursuant to chapter 16 of
this title.
SECTION 35. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, is amended by creating a new
chapter 33, entitled "Commissioner Regulated Professions".
- 61 - 017271

SECTION 36. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 33, is amended by adding
the following as a new part:
63-33-101. Chapter definitions.
As used in this chapter:
(1) "Commissioner" means the commissioner of health or a person to
whom the commissioner has delegated authority granted to the commissioner in
accordance with § 63-33-108;
(2) "Department" means the department of health;
(3) "Division" means the division of health related boards in the
department of health, as created by § 68-1-101;
(4) "License" means a certificate, registration, or license created in this
chapter; and
(5) "Licensee" means a person granted a certificate, registration, or
license pursuant to this chapter.
63-33-102. Creation – Commissioner's authority and duties – Rules.
(a) There is created an agency of commissioner issued licenses.
(b) The commissioner is responsible for all administrative, fiscal, and clerical
functions related to this chapter, which is accomplished through the division. All
documents and fees applicants or licensees are required to submit to the commissioner
by this chapter must be submitted to the division.
(c) For each of the licenses created by this chapter, the commissioner shall:
(1) Promulgate rules for the implementation of each part, including rules
to establish:
(A) Requirements and procedures for the issuance of licenses
and the renewal of licenses under each part;
(B) Standards of practice, ethics, advertising, and professional
responsibility to govern the conduct of persons licensed under each part;
- 62 - 017271

(C) Procedures for investigating reports of professional
misconduct and unlawful acts by persons licensed under each part; and
(D) Criteria and procedures for certification by endorsement and
reciprocity, waiver of examinations, and temporary certificates;
(2) Establish reasonable and necessary fees, including, but not limited to,
licensure and licensure renewal that, in the aggregate, cover the cost of
administering this chapter;
(3) Promulgate rules necessary for obtaining criminal background
information from applicants prior to the issuance of a license; and
(4) Issue all licenses approved by the commissioner and maintain a list of
persons holding licenses under each part, to be provided to any interested party
upon written request.
(d) The commissioner shall also:
(1) Receive complaints and review issues related to complaints and
disciplinary actions involving each person licensed under this chapter;
(2) Conduct investigations, as appropriate, of persons licensed pursuant
to this chapter;
(3) Review the qualifications of licensure applicants and issue licenses to
persons who meet the requirements for licensure under each part;
(4) Promulgate rules and criteria for licensee continuing education and
for the renewal of licenses;
(5) Issue private letter rulings in accordance with § 63-1-174;
(6) Promulgate rules and perform any other action required to
appropriately ensure the protection of the health, safety, and welfare of the public
as related to a license created by this chapter;
(7) Collect or receive all fees, fines, and moneys owed pursuant to this
chapter; and
- 63 - 017271

(8) Utilize screening panels in the investigative and disciplinary process
in the manner as follows:
(A) The screening panel must be made up of between one (1)
and three (3) commissioner-appointed consultants who have authority to
administer oaths to witnesses and deliberative privilege, and have the
same immunity as provided by law for board members;
(B) The members of the screening panel are not subject to
deposition or subpoena to testify regarding any matter or issue raised in a
contested case, criminal prosecution, or civil lawsuit that may result from
or be incident to the screening panel matters processed before them;
(C) Documents or records produced at the screening panel are
exempt from title 10, chapter 7, until there is a filing of a notice of charges
and such documents or records form the basis for such filing of a notice
of charges;
(D) The screening panel must be instructed as to the statutes and
rules pertaining to the disciplinary action and the procedures to be
followed by the panel, and provided Rule 31 of the Tennessee Supreme
Court for guidance on the principles of alternative dispute resolution;
(E) The commissioner does not have the authority to compel a
party to participate in a screening panel, and prejudice is not incurred if a
party chooses not to participate or accept the offer of the screening panel;
and
(F) The commissioner may promulgate rules regarding the
screening panel process.
(e) The rules promulgated by the commissioner for the implementation of each
part must comply with the Uniform Administrative Procedures Act, compiled in title 4,
chapter 5.
- 64 - 017271

(f) All moneys owed pursuant to this chapter, including the fees required by
applicants or licensees and the costs, fines, and penalties, assessed for a violation of
this chapter must be collected by the division. The division may maintain the existing
separate accounts established for the boards and registries that formerly licensed the
professions now licensed by the agency created by this chapter; provided, the division
combines the revenue collected such that the division may use the revenue of each
account to offset expenditures across the agency created by this chapter. Funds
remaining in these accounts at the end of any fiscal year do not revert to the general
fund but remain available for expenditure in accordance with law.
(g) The commissioner shall use the department-employed investigators,
inspectors, and agents, or use any other means necessary to bring about and maintain
the rigid administration and enforcement of this chapter and all laws regulating the
practice of the healings arts licensed by the commissioner.
63-33-103. License application.
(a) Applicants for a license created by this chapter shall submit an application on
the form created by the commissioner and any required fees to the division.
(b) In addition to the specific requirements for licensure of each part of this
chapter, the application must include evidence that the applicant meets the following
requirements:
(1) The applicant has attained the age of majority;
(2) The applicant is of good moral character and conducts the applicant's
professional activities in accordance with accepted professional and ethical
standards;
(3) The applicant has not had a professional credential refused, revoked,
suspended, or restricted and does not have a complaint, allegation, or
investigation pending in any regulatory jurisdiction in the United States or in
- 65 - 017271

another country for unprofessional conduct, and has not committed an act that
would constitute grounds for discipline of a license under § 63-33-106; and
(4) The applicant is either a citizen of the United States or a qualified
alien, as defined in § 4-58-102.
(c) The division and applicant shall comply with the criminal background check
requirements of § 63-1-116.
(d) All licensees shall comply with the requirements of § 63-1-109.
(e) Portions of an application involving an applicant's health condition, including
mental health conditions and substance use disorders, and records involving an
applicant's health condition, are confidential, privileged, and not public records subject to
inspection by citizens of this state, as described in § 10-7-503.
(f)
(1) When the division receives a completed application for initial
licensure from an applicant, the division shall, within sixty (60) days from the date
the division receives the completed application:
(A) Render a decision on the application; or
(B) Inform the applicant of the need to appear before the
commissioner or the commissioner's designee.
(2) As used in this subsection (f), "completed application" means an
application that satisfies all statutory and board rule requirements.
63-33-104. Reciprocity.
(a) The commissioner may, at the commissioner's discretion, grant a license
created by this chapter to a person residing or employed in this state who is certified or
licensed by a similar entity in another state whose standards, as determined by the
commissioner, are not less stringent than the standards required by the part creating the
license.
- 66 - 017271

(b) The commissioner may enter into a reciprocal agreement with another state
or jurisdiction that certifies or licenses persons engaged in the practice of a profession
licensed under this chapter if the commissioner determines that the other state has
substantially similar or more stringent certification or licensure requirements than this
state.
63-33-105. License renewal.
(a) A license issued under this chapter is valid for twenty-four (24) months from
the date of issuance and is renewable biennially at the end of the birth month of the
licensee.
(b) In addition to any requirements of this chapter creating the license, a
licensee requesting renewal of a certificate shall provide the following to the division in
advance of the expiration date of the license:
(1) A completed application on a form provided by the division and
payment of the fees set by the commissioner; and
(2) A certified or sworn statement that the licensee:
(A) Has completed all the continuing education hours required for
the licensee, whether required by statute or by rule, prior to the expiration
date of the license; and
(B) Has not had a professional credential revoked, suspended, or
restricted by a certification board, and does not have a complaint,
allegation, or investigation pending in this state or in any regulatory
jurisdiction for unethical or unprofessional conduct.
(c) If a licensee fails to submit an application for license renewal, to pay any fee
required by the commissioner, or to submit a certified or sworn statement as set forth in
subdivision (b)(2) prior to the expiration date of the license, then the license is
automatically revoked by the commissioner without further notice or hearing, unless
- 67 - 017271

renewal is completed and all fees are paid prior to the expiration of sixty (60) days from
the date of the expiration of the license.
(d) A person whose license is automatically revoked under this section may
apply in writing to the division for reinstatement of the license. Upon the showing of
good cause by the person and submitting documentation that all continuing education
requirements have been satisfied, the commissioner may reinstate the license upon the
payment of all fees set by the commissioner.
(e) Applicants and licensees must notify the division of the following within thirty
(30) days of their occurrence:
(1) A change of name, address, or other vital information;
(2) The filing of any criminal charge or civil action against the applicant or
licensee;
(3) The initiation of any disciplinary charges, investigations, findings, or
sanctions by a healthcare organization, federal or state agency, or other
professional association against the applicant or licensee; and
(4) Any other change in information provided by the applicant or licensee
to the division.
(f) For the purpose of effecting service of process upon a licensee, the
commissioner or the division may notify the licensee by certified mail, return receipt
requested, at the address on file with the division.
(g) A person licensed or certified to practice by this chapter who has retired or
may retire from such practice on or after the effective date of this act is not required to
register as is required by this chapter if the person files with the division an affidavit on a
form to be furnished by the division, stating the date on which the person retired from
such practice and such other facts as tend to verify the retirement as the division deems
necessary. If the person thereafter reengages in such practice in this state, then the
- 68 - 017271

person shall apply for licensure with the division as provided by this chapter and meet
other requirements as may be set by the commissioner.
63-33-106. License denial, suspension, or revocation – Grounds – Examinations –
Hearings.
(a) The commissioner has the power to:
(1) Deny an application for a license to any applicant who applies for the
same through reciprocity or otherwise;
(2) Permanently or temporarily withhold issuance of a license;
(3) Issue a license contingent upon such circumstances or requirements
as the commissioner may determine;
(4) Issue a conditional license that is limited or restricted for such time
and in such manner as the commissioner may determine, including a limited
license of temporary duration for applicants out of practice for an extended period
of time;
(5) Issue discipline to an applicant or licensee, or on a previously issued
license, including, but not limited to, any combination of, private censures and
warnings, public reprimands, limits, restrictions, conditions, probation periods,
suspension periods, require participation in a peer assistance program, and issue
civil penalties for such time and in such manner as the commissioner may deem
proper in the commissioner's discretion;
(6) Discipline a licensee who has been disciplined by another state of the
United States for any acts or omissions that would constitute grounds for
discipline licensed in this state, following the procedure in § 63-1-120; or
(7) Revoke, or permanently revoke, a license.
(b) The grounds upon which the commissioner may exercise the powers
enumerated in subsection (a) include, but are not limited to:
(1) Engaging in unprofessional, dishonorable, or unethical conduct;
- 69 - 017271

(2) Obtaining or attempting to obtain a license by making a false or
misleading statement, failing to make a required statement, or engaging in fraud
or deceit in any communication to the department;
(3) Violating or attempting to violate, directly or indirectly, or assisting in
or abetting the violation of, or conspiring to violate, a criminal statute of this state,
this part, a rule promulgated by the commissioner, or a lawful order of the
commissioner issued pursuant to rules;
(4) Engaging in gross professional liability, or a pattern of continued or
repeated professional liability, ignorance, negligence, or incompetence, in
professional work;
(5) Being habitually intoxicated or personally misusing drugs, or using
intoxicating liquors, narcotics, controlled substances, controlled substance
analogues, or other drugs or stimulants, in such manner as to adversely affect
the person's ability to safely practice in the person's profession;
(6) Being convicted of a felony, any offense under state or federal laws
relative to drugs or the professional practice, an offense involving moral
turpitude, or any offense for which the licensee or applicant is required to register
as a sexual offender or violent sexual offender pursuant to the Tennessee Sexual
Offender and Violent Sexual Offender Registration, Verification and Tracking Act
of 2004, compiled in title 40, chapter 39, part 2;
(7) Engaging in professional practice when mentally or physically unable
to do so safely; and
(8) Engaging in any other action deemed to be grounds for disciplinary
action under rules promulgated or enforced by the commissioner.
(c) All proceedings for disciplinary action against a licensee under this chapter
must be conducted in accordance with the Uniform Administrative Procedures Act,
compiled in title 4, chapter 5.
- 70 - 017271

(d) Assessment and collection of costs must follow the requirements and
procedure contained in § 63-1-144.
(e) In enforcing this section, the commissioner shall, upon probable cause, have
authority to compel an applicant or licensee to submit to a mental or physical
examination, or both, by a designated committee of at least three (3) practicing
physicians, including a psychiatrist where a question of mental condition is involved.
The applicant or licensee may have an independent medical practitioner present during
such examination, and the applicant may have an independent physical or mental
examination, which examination report must be filed with the commissioner for
consideration. The committee shall submit a report of its findings to the commissioner,
who must then hold a hearing governed by the Unform Administrative Procedures Act,
compiled in title 4, chapter 5.
(f) Notwithstanding § 63-1-122, for purposes of an action before the
commissioner for a license created and regulated under this chapter, in which the
standard of care is at issue, qualified expert testimony on the standard of care is
required. The standard of care for such actions is a statewide standard of minimal
competency and practice. The provisions of title 29, chapter 26, and specifically § 29-
26-115(a), concerning the locality rule, do not apply to disciplinary actions involving
licenses created under this chapter. However, expert testimony is not required to prove
a violation of unprofessional, dishonorable, or unethical conduct.
(g) A person whose license or certificate has been revoked by the commissioner
is not eligible to apply for reinstatement earlier than one (1) year from the date of
revocation.
63-33-107. Unlicensed practice.
(a) A person who engages in the practice of a profession licensed by the
commissioner without a current, valid license, and a person who violates this chapter,
- 71 - 017271

commits a Class B misdemeanor. Each such engagement in unlicensed practice
constitutes a separate offense.
(b) The commissioner may assess civil penalties against a person engaged in
the practice of a profession licensed by the commissioner without a current, valid license
for each separate offense. The commissioner may also refer the case to law
enforcement.
(c) The commissioner may petition any circuit or chancery court having
jurisdiction of a person within this state who is practicing without a license, to whom a
license has been denied, or whose license has been suspended or revoked, to enjoin
such person from continuing to practice the healing arts, or any branch thereof, within
this state. Jurisdiction is conferred upon the circuit and chancery courts of this state to
hear and determine all such causes as equity causes and exercise full and complete
jurisdiction in such injunctive proceedings.
(d) This section does not confer criminal jurisdiction upon a court not now
possessing such criminal jurisdiction, nor does any such court, as an incident to the
injunctive proceedings authorized in this section, have the power to assess the criminal
penalties set out in this chapter.
63-33-108. Delegation of powers.
(a) The commissioner may delegate any of the powers granted to the
commissioner in this chapter to any employee of the department. The commissioner
may also appoint consultant members of any health-licensed profession to work for a per
diem or hourly rate to review and evaluate licensure applications, disciplinary cases,
licensee inquiries, serve on state or national advisory boards or compact commissions,
and otherwise assist division staff as necessary to carry out this chapter.
(b) When appointing consultants pursuant to this section, the commissioner shall
consider recommendations made by interested professional associations related to the
licensure type at issue for the consultant's review.
- 72 - 017271

63-33-109. Fees.
(a) By rule, the commissioner shall establish fees for all the license types
created under this chapter. These fees include, but are not limited to:
(1) Initial licensure application fee;
(2) Examination fee;
(3) Biennial licensure renewal fee;
(4) Late renewal fee;
(5) Licensure reinstatement fee;
(6) Duplicate decorative license fee; and
(7) Reciprocal licensure fee.
(b) The commissioner shall ensure that the fees collected by the division for the
agency of commissioner issued licenses are sufficient in an amount to pay all the costs
associated with the administration, monitoring, and enforcement for all the licenses
created under this chapter.
63-33-110. Emergency rules.
To effectuate this chapter, the commissioner may promulgate emergency rules
pursuant to § 4-5-208(a)(5).
63-33-111. Validity of prior licenses, certificates, and registrations.
All licenses, certificates, and registrations regulated under chapters 18, 24, 27,
and 31, and valid as of June 30, 2026, must be transferred to the agency of
commissioner issued licenses and remain in effect on their current renewal cycles under
the authority of the commissioner pending the promulgation of any new rules on the
issuance and renewal of such licenses, certificates, and registrations, as necessary.
63-33-112. Transfer of rules and regulatory authority to the commissioner.
(a) As of July 1, 2026, the secretary of state shall cause the following rules to be
transferred to Tenn. Comp. R. & Regs. 1200-10:
(1) Tenn. Comp. R. & Regs. 0150-01;
- 73 - 017271

(2) Tenn. Comp. R. & Regs. 0870-01 and 0870-02;
(3) Tenn. Comp. R. & Regs. 1330-01;
(4) Tenn. Comp. R. & Regs. 0880-14;
(5) Tenn. Comp. R. & Regs. 0880-12;
(6) All rules promulgated by the [former] professional art therapist
advisory committee of the board of examiners in psychology [repealed]; and
(7) All rules promulgated by the [former] professional music therapy
advisory committee of the board of examiners in psychology [repealed].
(b) The rules listed in subsection (a) must remain in effect pending the
promulgation of any new rules on the same subject in accordance with the Uniform
Administrative Procedures Act, compiled in title 4, chapter 5.
(c) Effective July 1, 2026, the commissioner has the authority to regulate the
professions affected by the rules listed in subsection (a), including through use of those
rules, until new rules on the same subject are promulgated.
SECTION 37. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 33, is amended by adding
the following as a new part:
63-33-201. Part definitions.
As used in this part, unless the context otherwise requires:
(1) "Compensation" means the payment, loan, advance, donation,
contribution, deposit, or gift of money or anything of value;
(2) "Massage," "bodywork," and "somatic" mean the manipulation of the
soft tissues of the body with the intention of positively affecting the health and
well-being of the client;
(3) "Massage establishment" means a place of business held out to the
public wherein massage is practiced; and
(4) "Massage therapist" means a person who practices massage for
compensation and is licensed by the commissioner.
- 74 - 017271

63-33-202. Practice of massage – Practice of reflexology.
(a) Persons or massage establishments engaged in massage for compensation
must be licensed by the commissioner.
(b) It is unlawful to use the word "massage," or any other term that implies
massage technique or method, when advertising a service by a person who is not
licensed under this part or another chapter of state law.
(c) The practice of reflexology is not subject to the licensure requirements of this
chapter. As used in this subsection (c), "reflexology" means the application of specific
pressures to reflex points in the hands and feet only.
63-33-203. Documentation required from applicants.
(a)
(1) Except as provided in subdivision (a)(2) and in addition to the
requirements of § 63-33-103, each applicant for licensure as a massage therapist
shall provide documentation in the form required by the commissioner that the
applicant:
(A) Successfully completed the curriculum or curricula of one (1)
or more postsecondary academic institutions for massage, bodywork, or
somatic therapy as defined by board rules, totaling six hundred fifty (650)
hours or more, such institutions being approved by the commissioner
pursuant to § 63-33-209, and either authorized by the Tennessee higher
education commission, or its equivalent in other states, or approved, or
under the governance of, the board of regents; and
(B) Received a passing score on a competency examination
approved by the board.
(2)
(A) A person who has completed a program of study as required
by subdivision (a)(1)(A) in a postsecondary academic institution located in
- 75 - 017271

this state and received a diploma or certificate prior to September 1,
2005, must be issued a license without completing the examination
requirement in subdivision (a)(1)(B).
(B) A person who meets the requirements of subdivision (a)(2)(A)
has until January 1, 2006, to apply for such a license.
(C) Persons licensed under this subdivision (a)(2) are not
considered to have national certification and not hold themselves out to
be nationally certified.
(b) In addition to the requirements of § 63-33-103, each applicant for licensure
as a massage establishment shall provide documentation in the form required by the
commissioner that each person engaged in massage at the massage establishment has
provided the documentation required in subsection (a) and has been licensed as a
massage therapist by the commissioner.
(c) Notwithstanding this part, an establishment license is not required for the
office of a physician licensed under chapter 4, 6, or 9 of this title if a massage for
compensation is provided within that office by a licensed massage therapist.
63-33-204. Inspections.
In order to effectuate this part, the commissioner may conduct an investigation of
persons engaged in massage and massage establishments and inspect the license of
practitioners and establishments for compliance. The refusal of a practitioner or
establishment to permit inspections is grounds for revocation, suspension, or refusal to
issue a license pursuant to this part.
63-33-205. Exempted persons.
This part does not affect, prevent, or restrict:
(1) Persons qualified and licensed to practice other health professions
from engaging in the practice of massage when incidental to the practice of their
profession;
- 76 - 017271

(2) Persons qualified and licensed to practice as barbers or
cosmetologists from engaging in the practice of massage when incidental to the
practice of their profession;
(3) Students enrolled in an institution described in § 63-33-203(a)(1) or a
public school of this state; provided, that the student does not hold the student's
self out as a licensed massage therapist and does not receive compensation for
massage; and
(4) Massage therapists licensed in other states or countries when
providing educational programs or services for a period of time not to exceed
thirty (30) days within a calendar year.
63-33-206. Temporary license.
(a) The commissioner may, in the commissioner's discretion, grant a temporary
license to a person who has been licensed, registered, or certified, in good standing, in
another state, territory of the United States, or the District of Columbia, that meets all
other requirements for reciprocity under this chapter and rules promulgated pursuant to
this chapter, but which does not require successful passage of a competency
examination approved by the commissioner.
(b) A person granted a temporary license pursuant to this section may work if
the person is at all times working under the supervision of a person licensed pursuant to
§ 63-33-203.
(c)
(1) A temporary license issued pursuant to this section expires six (6)
months after the date of issuance.
(2) A person granted a temporary license pursuant to this section may
apply for one (1) extension of the person's temporary license for an additional six
(6) months if:
(A)
- 77 - 017271

(i) The person has been unable to take a competency
exam approved by the commissioner within the initial temporary
license period; and
(ii) Is registered to take an upcoming competency exam
approved by the commissioner; or
(B) The person is still waiting for the results of the most recent
competency exam approved by the commissioner.
63-33-207. Massage deemed medically therapeutic – Taxation.
Notwithstanding a law to the contrary, the act of a duly licensed massage
therapist in performing a massage is deemed to be medically therapeutic in nature and
not subject to the collection of any form of state or local taxation regulations not also
imposed on other medically therapeutic activities.
63-33-208. Designation as "primary care provider" prohibited.
A person licensed by the commissioner under this part must not be referred to as
a primary care provider or permitted to use such designation.
63-33-209. Powers and duties of commissioner – Passage rate of schools of
massage therapy.
In addition to the powers and duties granted to or imposed by this chapter, the
commissioner has the following powers and duties:
(1) To prescribe the minimum curricular and minimum standards for
schools of massage therapy and for courses of training that prepare individuals
for licensure under this part;
(2) To approve such schools and courses as meet the requirements of
this part and the rules of the commissioner;
(3) To issue certificates of approval to such schools and courses that
meet the requirements of this part and the rules of the commissioner;
- 78 - 017271

(4) To conduct hearings for disciplinary action against schools or courses
that fail to meet the minimum requirements of this part and the rules of the
commissioner; and
(5) To annually publish passage rates for each school of massage
therapy, based upon the results of each student's success in taking a national
examination approved by the commissioner. Schools that fail to achieve an
overall passing rate of seventy percent (70%) are required to submit a remedial
plan to be approved by the commissioner.
63-33-210. Alternative licensure process.
(a) The commissioner may issue a license to practice massage therapy to an
applicant who:
(1) Meets the qualifications set forth in § 63-33-103; and
(2) Has been certified by the National Certification Board for Therapeutic
Massage and Bodywork for the five-year period immediately preceding
application for licensure and can submit documentation satisfactory to the
commissioner that the applicant has engaged in the practice of massage therapy
in another state for the five-year period immediately preceding application for
licensure, and who either:
(A) Has met the qualifications set forth in § 63-33-203(a), but is
unable, because the educational institution either was not state approved
or is no longer in existence, to produce a transcript to document
compliance; or
(B) Graduated from a qualified massage school or course prior to
October 1, 1995.
(b) The commissioner may promulgate rules that are necessary to effectuate this
section.
- 79 - 017271

SECTION 38. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 33, is amended by adding
the following as a new part:
63-33-301. Part definitions.
As used in this part, unless the context otherwise requires:
(1) "Athletic injury" means an injury sustained by a person as a result of
the person's participation in exercises, sports, games, or recreation requiring
physical strength, agility, flexibility, range of motion, speed, or stamina, or
comparable athletic injury that prevents the person from participating in such
activities; and
(2) "Athletic trainer" means a person with specific qualifications as set
forth in this part, who, upon the advice, consent, and oral or written prescriptions
or referrals of a physician licensed under this title, carries out the practice of
prevention, recognition, evaluation, management, disposition, treatment, or
rehabilitation of athletic injuries, and, in carrying out these functions, the athletic
trainer may use physical modalities, such as heat, light, sound, cold, electricity,
or mechanical devices related to prevention, recognition, evaluation,
management, disposition, rehabilitation, and treatment; an athletic trainer shall
practice only in those areas in which such athletic trainer is competent by reason
of training or experience that can be substantiated by records or other evidence
found acceptable by the board in the exercise of the commissioner's considered
discretion.
63-33-302. Prohibited representations as an athletic trainer.
(a) A person shall not represent the person's self as, or claim to be, an athletic
trainer or perform, for compensation, any of the activities of an athletic trainer without
first obtaining a license under this part.
(b) This part does not prevent a person from serving as a student-trainer, or a
similar position, if such service is not primarily for compensation and is carried out under
- 80 - 017271

the supervision of an athletic trainer duly licensed as provided in this part and a
physician licensed under this title. Such supervision must be provided under the
guidelines of the National Athletic Trainers' Association (NATA) Board of Certification,
Inc., or approved by the commissioner.
63-33-303. Documentation required from applicants.
In addition to the requirements of § 63-33-103, an applicant for an athletic trainer
license shall provide documentation in the form required by the commissioner that the
applicant:
(1) Has met the athletic training curriculum requirements of a college or
university approved by the commissioner; and
(2) Has satisfactorily completed all of the National Athletic Trainers'
Association (NATA) Board of Certification, Inc., qualifications and is certified as
an athletic trainer in good standing by the NATA Board of Certification, Inc., or
approved by the commissioner.
63-33-304. Exempted persons.
(a) This part does not limit or prevent a person duly licensed or certified under
the laws of this state from practicing the profession for which the person was licensed or
certified.
(b) This part does not apply to a person engaging in the practice of athletic
training while employed for such purpose by a postsecondary educational institution or
professional athletic organization from another state that is temporarily present in this
state for an athletic competition or exhibition.
(c) This part does not apply to physicians duly licensed under this title who
employ or contract for services provided by persons in the physician's office assisting in
the care of patients and rendered under the supervision, control, and responsibility of the
licensed physician.
63-33-305. Civil penalties.
- 81 - 017271

The commissioner has the authority to assess civil penalties commensurate with
those assessable under § 63-1-134 against persons who have knowingly employed,
contracted for, or otherwise utilized unlicensed persons in the practice of athletic
training, with or without compensation.
63-33-306. Athletic trainers – Scope of practice.
(a) An athletic trainer may use dry needling, as defined in § 63-13-103, and
physical modalities, such as heat, light, sound, cold, electricity, or mechanical devices,
for the prevention, recognition, evaluation, management, disposition, rehabilitation, and
treatment of athletic injuries.
(b) An athletic trainer shall only practice in those areas in which an athletic
trainer is competent by reason of training or experience that can be substantiated by
records or other evidence found acceptable by the board in the exercise of the
commissioner's considered discretion.
(c) An athletic trainer shall obtain such training and certification in the practice of
dry needling as the commissioner may require by rule. The practice of dry needling by
an athletic trainer under this chapter does not constitute the practice of acupuncture
under part 4 of this chapter.
(d) The commissioner is authorized to promulgate rules to effectuate this
section. The rules must be promulgated in accordance with the Uniform Administrative
Procedures Act, compiled in title 4, chapter 5.
SECTION 39. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 33, is amended by adding
the following as a new part:
63-33-401. Part definitions.
As used in this part, unless the context otherwise requires:
(1) "ACAOM" means the Accreditation Commission for Acupuncture and
Oriental Medicine;
- 82 - 017271

(2) "Acupuncture" means a form of health care developed from traditional
and modern oriental medical concepts that employs oriental medical diagnosis
and treatment and adjunctive therapies and diagnostic techniques for the
promotion, maintenance, and restoration of health and the prevention of disease.
"Adjunctive therapies" within the scope of "acupuncture" may include
acupressure, cupping, thermal, and electrical treatment and the recommendation
of dietary guidelines and supplements and therapeutic exercise based on
traditional oriental medical concepts;
(3) "ADS" means an acupuncture detoxification specialist trained in, and
who performs only, the five-point auricular detoxification treatment;
(4) "NADA" means the National Acupuncture Detoxification Association;
(5) "NCCAOM" means the National Certification Commission for
Acupuncture and Oriental Medicine; and
(6) "Practice of acupuncture" means the insertion of acupuncture needles
and the application of moxibustion to specific areas of the human body based on
oriental medical diagnosis as a primary mode of therapy.
63-33-402. Exempted persons – Unlawful practice of acupuncture – Limited
licensure.
(a) This part does not apply to:
(1) Physicians licensed under chapter 6 or chapter 9 of this title, and
does not prevent the practice of acupuncture by such physicians or to prevent
such physicians from using the title "acupuncturist";
(2) Registered nurses who are nationally certified as holistic nurses and
who have successfully completed an accredited education program in
acupuncture; or
(3) Chiropractic physicians licensed under chapter 4 of this title, and
does not prevent the practice of acupuncture by chiropractic physicians who
- 83 - 017271

have completed two hundred fifty (250) hours of an accredited acupuncture
course and have passed the National Board of Chiropractic Examiners
acupuncture exam.
(b) It is otherwise unlawful to practice acupuncture for compensation or
gratuitously unless licensed under this part. This restriction does not apply to the
following:
(1) Students practicing acupuncture under the supervision of a licensed
acupuncturist as part of a course of study approved by the commissioner; or
(2) Individuals who do not otherwise possess the credentials required for
the practice of acupuncture by this part, or rules promulgated under this part, by
the commissioner are granted limited licensure as an ADS for the purpose of the
treatment of alcoholism, substance abuse, or chemical dependency if they meet
the following conditions:
(A) Provide documentation of successful completion of a
commissioner-approved training program in auricular detoxification
acupuncture that meets or exceeds standards of training set by NADA;
(B) Practice auricular detoxification treatment in a hospital, clinic,
or treatment facility that provides comprehensive alcohol and substance
abuse or chemical dependency services, including counseling, under the
supervision of a licensed acupuncturist or medical director;
(C) Satisfy all appropriate ethical standards; and
(D) Limit their practice to the five-point auricular detoxification
treatment.
63-33-403. Documentation required from applicants.
(a) In addition to the requirements of § 63-33-103, an applicant for licensure as
an acupuncturist shall provide documentation in the form required by the commissioner
that the applicant:
- 84 - 017271

(1) Has successfully completed a three-year postsecondary training
program or acupuncture college program that is ACAOM-accredited or in
candidacy status or that meets ACAOM's standards;
(2) Has successfully completed an NCCAOM-approved clean needle
technique course; and
(3) Either:
(A) Has current active status as a diplomate in acupuncture of the
NCCAOM; or
(B) Has current state licensure in good standing by another state
with substantially equivalent or higher standards.
(b) The commissioner shall issue a limited acupuncture license to an ADS who
meets the requirements listed in § 63-33-402(b)(2).
63-33-404. License renewals.
In addition to the requirements of § 63-33-105, in order to renew a license, a
person shall submit proof of current active NCCAOM certification in acupuncture or
document compliance with § 63-33-403. To renew an ADS license, a person shall
submit proof of current active practice in auricular detoxification treatment, as
determined by the commissioner.
63-33-405. Health practices.
(a) All licensed individuals under this part shall use only presterilized, disposable
needles in their administration of acupuncture treatments. The use of staples in the
practice of acupuncture is prohibited.
(b) Health practices must include:
(1) Hands being washed with soap and water or other disinfectant before
handling needles and between treatment of different patients;
(2) Skin in the area of penetration being thoroughly swabbed with alcohol
or other germicidal solution before inserting needles; and
- 85 - 017271

(3) Individuals passing a nationally recognized clean needle technique
course before being allowed to practice acupuncture and related techniques.
63-33-406. Use of titles "licensed acupuncturist" or "ADS".
The titles "licensed acupuncturist" or "ADS" may be used by persons licensed
under this part. A person who is not properly licensed to practice medicine or
osteopathic medicine shall not use licensure under this part to identify the person as a
doctor or physician.
SECTION 40. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 33, is amended by adding
the following as a new part:
63-33-501. Practice of art therapy.
(a) The practice of art therapy in this state is declared to affect the public health,
safety, and welfare of citizens of this state.
(b) The commissioner is authorized to protect the public from:
(1) The practice of art therapy by unqualified persons; and
(2) Unprofessional, unethical, and harmful conduct by art therapy
practitioners.
(c) A person shall not represent to be or function as a professional art therapist
in this state unless the person holds a valid license issued by the commissioner. The
commissioner shall also regulate the practice of art therapy.
63-33-502. Part definitions.
As used in this part:
(1) "Appraisal activities":
(A) Means selecting, administering, scoring, and interpreting art
therapy instruments that are used to understand, measure, or facilitate an
individual's normal human growth and development; and
(B) Does not include the use of projective techniques in the
assessment of personality, nor the use of psychological or clinical tests
- 86 - 017271

designed to identify or classify abnormal or pathological human behavior,
nor the use of individually administered intelligence tests;
(2) "Art therapy" means the integrated application of psychotherapeutic
principles and methods with specialized training in visual art media, the
neurobiological implications of art-making and the creative process, and art-
based assessment models to assist individuals, families, or groups to improve
mental functioning, increase self-awareness and self-esteem, resolve conflicts
and distress, and enhance social functioning;
(3) "Art therapy certified supervisor" means a person credentialed by the
Art Therapy Credentials Board, Inc., to provide supervised clinical experience for
an associate art therapist;
(4) "Associate art therapist" means a person holding a master's or
doctoral degree in art therapy while engaged in the practice of professional art
therapy under supervision as part of clinical training to fulfill the supervised
experience requirement for becoming a licensed professional art therapist;
(5) "Certified art therapist" means a person holding national board
certification (ATR-BC) from the Art Therapy Credentials Board, Inc.;
(6) "Credentialed art therapist" means a person holding credentials in
good standing with the Art Therapy Credentials Board, Inc., as a registered art
therapist (ATR), certified art therapist (ATR-BC), or art therapy certified
supervisor;
(7) "Licensed professional art therapist" means a person who is licensed
to practice professional art therapy in this state;
(8) "Practice of professional art therapy":
(A) Means rendering or offering to render to individuals, groups,
organizations, or the general public any service as an independent or
- 87 - 017271

adjunctive therapist involving the application of art therapy principles,
techniques, methods, or procedures; and
(B) Includes, but is not limited to, therapeutic interventions to
facilitate alternative modes of receptive and expressive communication,
development of treatment plans, appraisal activities, consulting and
referral activities, and prevention and treatment of mental and emotional
conditions; and
(9) "Supervision" means the regular observation and oversight of the
functions and activities of a graduate art therapy student as part of an internship
or practicum experience, or an associate art therapist engaged in the practice of
art therapy to fulfill the requirements for licensure under § 63-33-503.
63-33-503. Documentation required from applicants.
(a) In addition to the requirements of § 63-33-103, an applicant for licensure
under this part shall provide documentation in the form required by the commissioner
that the applicant has:
(1) Passed the board certification examination of the Art Therapy
Credentials Board, Inc.; and
(2) Either:
(A) Received a master's degree or doctoral degree in art therapy
from a program approved by the American Art Therapy Association or
accredited by the Commission on Accreditation of Allied Health Education
Programs at the time the degree was conferred, and has completed no
less than one thousand (1,000) client contact hours of experience after
the master's degree was conferred under the supervision of an art
therapy certified supervisor, licensed professional art therapist,
credentialed art therapist, or other licensed mental health professional
approved by the commissioner. At least one-half (1/2) of the required
- 88 - 017271

supervision hours must be provided by an art therapy certified supervisor,
licensed professional art therapist, or certified art therapist; or
(B) Received a master's degree or doctoral degree from a college
or university that was accredited by a national or regional accrediting
organization recognized by the Council for Higher Education Accreditation
in a program with a graduate-level course of study and clinical training
that, as determined by the commissioner, is equivalent to an approved or
accredited program in art therapy, and has completed not less than one
thousand five hundred (1,500) hours of client contact experience after the
qualifying degree was conferred under the supervision of an art therapy
certified supervisor, licensed professional art therapist, credentialed art
therapist, or other licensed mental health professional approved by the
commissioner. At least one-half (1/2) of the required supervision hours
must be provided by an art therapy certified supervisor, licensed
professional art therapist, or certified art therapist.
(b) A person holding a national credential in good standing as a certified art
therapist is deemed to have met the requirements of this section upon submitting an
application and fee and providing evidence satisfying the requirements of § 63-33-103 in
the form required by the commissioner.
63-33-504. Use of title "licensed professional art therapist" or "licensed art
therapist."
(a) A person shall not use the title "licensed professional art therapist" or
"licensed art therapist," or use an abbreviation to indicate or imply that the person is a
licensed professional art therapist in this state unless the person holds a license issued
by the commissioner under this part. This subsection (a) does not prohibit an associate
art therapist from using the title "associate art therapist" in accordance with this part.
(b) A person shall not practice professional art therapy unless the person is:
- 89 - 017271

(1) Licensed by the commissioner as a licensed professional art
therapist;
(2) An associate art therapist, as long as the person uses the title of
"associate art therapist" and does not represent themselves to the public as a
licensed professional art therapist; or
(3) Exempt from licensure under § 63-33-506.
63-33-505. Authorized work settings.
(a) A licensed professional art therapist may practice independently for and with
organizations that include, but are not limited to, addiction and rehabilitation centers, art
studios and centers, behavioral health hospitals and outpatient settings, cancer
treatment centers, community centers, community services boards, correctional facilities,
disability services, eating disorder clinics, government agencies, medical hospitals and
outpatient settings, military bases and veterans and family services, museums,
nonprofits, nursing homes, physical rehabilitation, residential treatment centers, schools,
senior living facilities, state programs, and wellness centers.
(b) Until the commissioner promulgates rules to establish the requirements for
private outpatient independent practice by a licensed professional art therapist, a
licensed professional art therapist shall only work in a private, outpatient independent
setting if the patient is referred to the therapist by:
(1) A physician licensed under chapter 6 or 9 of this title;
(2) A psychologist licensed under chapter 11 of this title;
(3) A professional counselor licensed under chapter 22 of this title;
(4) A professional counselor designated as a mental health service
provider under chapter 22 of this title;
(5) A marital and family therapist licensed under chapter 22 of this title;
(6) A pastoral counselor licensed under chapter 22 of this title;
- 90 - 017271

(7) A licensed master's social worker licensed under chapter 23 of this
title;
(8) A licensed clinical social worker licensed under chapter 23 of this title;
or
(9) Another advanced medical or mental health professional licensed
under this title, as determined by the commissioner.
63-33-506. Authorized activities.
(a) This part does not:
(1) Require licensure or restrict the activities of a student enrolled in a
graduate program in art therapy approved by the commissioner while practicing
art therapy under qualified supervision and as part of an approved course of
study; or
(2) Prohibit or restrict the practice of persons authorized to practice under
this title who perform services consistent with the scope of practice of their
profession and within the scope of their training and competence if the persons
do not represent themselves to the public as a professional art therapist or as
holding a license issued under this part.
(b) This part does not permit any method of treatment that involves the
administration or prescription of drugs or the practice of medicine in this state or permits
a person licensed as a professional art therapist to perform psychological testing.
(c) Subsection (b) does not prohibit a licensed professional art therapist from
conducting appraisal activities. Consistent with each licensed professional art therapist's
formal education and training, licensed professional art therapists may administer and
utilize appropriate art therapy assessment instruments that measure or determine
problems or dysfunctions within the context of human growth and development as part of
the therapeutic process or in the development of a treatment plan.
- 91 - 017271

SECTION 41. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 33, is amended by adding
the following as a new part:
63-33-601. Practice of music therapy.
(a) The practice of music therapy in this state is declared to affect the public
health, safety, and welfare of citizens of this state.
(b) The commissioner is authorized and given the duty to protect the public from:
(1) The practice of clinical music therapy by unqualified persons; and
(2) Unprofessional, unethical, and harmful conduct by music therapy
practitioners.
(c) A person shall not represent to be or function as a professional music
therapist in this state unless the person holds a valid license issued by the
commissioner. The commissioner shall also regulate the practice of music therapy.
(d) This part does not restrict the non-clinical, non-therapeutic music intervention
of the Tennessee person-centered music program administered by the Tennessee
commission on aging and disability, created by § 52-8-102, and associated area
agencies on aging and disability or their representatives.
63-33-602. Part definitions.
As used in this part:
(1) "Certified professional music therapist" means a person certified to
practice music therapy under this part;
(2) "Music intervention" means the use of music in an individualized
approach that includes music improvisation, receptive music listening, song
writing, lyric discussion, music and imagery, singing, music performance,
learning through music, music combined with other arts, music-assisted
relaxation, music-based education, electronic music technology, adapted music
intervention, and movement to music, that may be used in a clinical, therapeutic
relationship or in a non-clinical, nontherapeutic manner; and
- 92 - 017271

(3) "Music therapy":
(A) Means the clinical and evidence-based use of music
interventions to accomplish individualized goals for people of all ages and
ability levels within a therapeutic relationship by a board-certified music
therapist; and
(B) Does not include the screening, diagnosis, or assessment of
any physical, mental, or communication disorder.
63-33-603. Rules.
In addition to the authority granted by and requirements found in part 1 of this
chapter, the rules promulgated by the commissioner for the implementation of this part
must:
(1) Provide for the requirements for licensure as set forth in § 63-33-604;
and
(2) Take into consideration the standards of ethics and professional
conduct of the code of ethics of the American Music Therapy Association and
code of professional ethics of the Certification Board for Music Therapists in
effect on January 1, 2025, or any successor organization.
63-33-604. Documentation required from applicants.
In addition to the requirements of § 63-33-103, the applicant shall provide
documentation in the form required by the commissioner that the applicant:
(1) Holds a bachelor's degree or higher in music therapy, or its
equivalent, including clinical training hours from a music therapy program within
an accredited college or university;
(2) Has passed the examination for board certification offered by the
Certification Board for Music Therapists, or any successor organization, or
provides proof of being transitioned into board certification; and
(3) Is currently a board-certified music therapist.
- 93 - 017271

63-33-605. Use of title "certified professional music therapist" or "certified music
therapist."
(a) A person shall not use the title "certified professional music therapist," or
"certified music therapist," or use any abbreviation to indicate that the person is certified
as a professional music therapist in this state unless the person holds a certificate
issued by the commissioner under this part.
(b) Subsection (a) does not prohibit:
(1) A person who is licensed, certified, or regulated under the laws of this
state in another profession or occupation, including physicians, psychologists,
psychoanalysts, registered nurses, marriage and family therapists, social
workers, occupational therapists, professional or rehabilitation counselors,
speech-language pathologists or audiologists, or personnel supervised by a
licensed professional from performing work, including the use of music, that is
incidental to the practice of the person's licensed, certified, or regulated
profession or occupation, if the person does not represent themself as a music
therapist;
(2) A person whose training and national certification attests to the
person's preparation and ability to practice their certified profession or
occupation, if the person does not represent themself as a music therapist;
(3) A practice of music therapy as an integral part of a program of study
for students enrolled in an accredited music therapy program, if the student does
not represent themself as a music therapist;
(4) A person who practices music therapy under the supervision of a
certified professional music therapist, if the person does not represent themself
as a music therapist; or
(5) The use of music intervention in a non-clinical, non-therapeutic
manner by persons who do not represent themselves as music therapists or
- 94 - 017271

through a program that is not represented to be a music therapy program,
including the Tennessee person-centered music program administered by the
Tennessee commission on aging and disability, created by § 52-8-102.
63-33-606. Authorized work settings – Required reviews.
(a) A certified professional music therapist may practice independently for and
with organizations that include, but are not limited to, addiction and rehabilitation
centers, music studios and centers, behavioral health hospitals and outpatient settings,
cancer treatment centers, community centers, community services boards, correctional
facilities, disability services, eating disorder clinics, government agencies, medical
hospitals and outpatient settings, military bases and veterans and family services,
museums, nonprofits, nursing homes, physical rehabilitation, residential treatment
centers, schools, senior living facilities, state programs, and wellness centers.
(b)
(1)
(A) Before a certified professional music therapist provides music
therapy services to a client for an identified clinical or developmental
need, the certified professional music therapist shall review the client's
diagnosis, treatment needs, and treatment plan with the healthcare
providers involved in the client's care.
(B) During the provision of music therapy services to a client, the
certified professional music therapist shall collaborate, as applicable, with
the client's treatment team, including the client's physician, psychologist,
licensed clinical social worker, or other mental health professional.
During the provision of music therapy services to a client with a
communication disorder, the certified professional music therapist shall
collaborate and discuss the music therapy treatment plan with the client's
- 95 - 017271

audiologist or speech-Ianguage pathologist so that a music therapist may
work with the client and address communication skills.
(2) Before a certified professional music therapist provides music therapy
services to a student for an identified educational need in a special education
setting, the certified professional music therapist shall review the student's
diagnosis, treatment needs, and treatment plan with the individualized family
service plan or individualized education program team.
(3) When providing educational or healthcare services, a certified
professional music therapist shall not replace the services provided by an
audiologist or a speech-language pathologist. Unless authorized to practice
speech-language pathology, music therapists shall not evaluate, examine, or
provide instruction or counsel on speech, language, communication, and
swallowing disorders and conditions. A person certified as a professional music
therapist shall not represent to the public that the person is authorized to treat a
communication disorder. This subdivision (b)(3) does not prohibit a person,
certified as a professional music therapist from representing to the public that the
person is qualified to work with clients with communication disorders and to
address communication skills.
63-33-607. Authorized activities.
In addition to any other authority granted under this part, certified professional
music therapists may:
(1) Accept referrals for music therapy services from medical,
developmental, mental health, or education professionals; family members;
clients; caregivers; or others involved with and authorized to provide client
services;
(2) Conduct a music therapy assessment of a client to determine if
treatment is indicated. If treatment is indicated, then the certified professional
- 96 - 017271

music therapist may collect systematic, comprehensive, and accurate information
to determine the appropriateness and type of music therapy services to provide
for the client;
(3) Develop an individualized music therapy treatment plan for the client
that is based upon the results of the music therapy assessment. The music
therapy treatment plan must include individualized goals and objectives that
focus on the assessed needs and strengths of the client and specify the music
therapy approaches and interventions to be used to address these goals and
objectives;
(4) Implement an individualized music therapy treatment plan that is
consistent with any other developmental, rehabilitative, habilitative, medical,
mental health, preventive, wellness care, or educational services being provided
to the client;
(5) Evaluate a client's response to music therapy and the music therapy
treatment plan, documenting change and progress, and suggesting
modifications, as appropriate;
(6) Develop a plan for determining when the provision of music therapy
services is no longer needed in collaboration with the client, physician, or other
provider of health care or education of the client, family members of the client,
and any other appropriate person upon whom the client relies for support;
(7) Minimize barriers to ensure that the client receives music therapy
services in the least restrictive environment;
(8) Collaborate with and educate the client and the family, caregiver of
the client, or any other appropriate person regarding the needs of the client that
are being addressed in music therapy and the manner in which the music
therapy treatment addresses those needs; and
- 97 - 017271

(9) Utilize their appropriate knowledge and skills to practice, which
include the use of research, reasoning, and problem-solving skills in determining
appropriate actions in the context of each clinical setting.
63-33-608. Psychological practice.
This part does not permit a certified professional music therapist to engage in a
psychological practice as described in chapter 11, part 2 of this title.
SECTION 42. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 33, is amended by adding
the following as a new part:
63-33-801. Part definitions – Setting for practice of polysomnography.
(a) As used in this part, unless the context otherwise requires:
(1) "Direct supervision" means that the polysomnographic technologist
providing supervision must be present in the area where the polysomnographic
procedure is being performed and immediately available to furnish assistance
and direction throughout the performance of the procedure;
(2) "General supervision" means that the polysomnographic procedure is
provided under a physician's overall direction and control, but the physician's
presence is not required during the performance of the procedure;
(3) "Polysomnographic student" means a person who is enrolled in an
educational program that is accredited by the Commission on Accreditation of
Allied Health Education Programs (CAAHEP), as provided in § 63-33-803(a)(1),
and who may provide sleep-related services under the direct supervision of a
polysomnographic technologist as a part of the person's educational program;
(4) "Polysomnographic technician" means a person who has graduated
from an accredited educational program described in § 63-33-803(a)(1) but has
not yet passed the national certifying examination given by the Board of
Registered Polysomnographic Technologists, who has obtained a temporary
- 98 - 017271

permit from the commissioner, and who may provide sleep-related services
under the general supervision of a licensed physician;
(5) "Polysomnographic technologist" means a person who is credentialed
by the Board of Registered Polysomnographic Technologists and is licensed by
the commissioner to engage in the practice of polysomnography under the
general supervision of a licensed physician;
(6) "Polysomnographic trainee" means a person who is enrolled in an
accredited sleep technologist education program (A-STEP) that is accredited by
the American Academy of Sleep Medicine and who may provide sleep-related
services under the direct supervision of a polysomnographic technologist as a
part of the person's educational program;
(7) "Practice of polysomnography" means the staging and scoring of
sleep by continuous and simultaneous monitoring of the stages of sleep and
wake through use of an electroencephalogram (EEG), an electrooculogram
(EOG), and a submental electromyogram (EMG), in conjunction with the
recording and monitoring of other physiological variables, and the assignment of
values for duration, frequency, and type of event to each stage of sleep in which
the event occurred. The following tasks are considered a part of the practice of
polysomnography only when performed as part of the staging and scoring of
sleep under the general supervision of a licensed physician:
(A) Monitoring and recording physiologic data during the
evaluation of sleep-related disorders, including sleep-related respiratory
disturbances, by applying the following techniques, equipment, and
procedures:
(i) Continuous or bilevel positive airway pressure titration
on spontaneously breathing patients using a mask or oral
- 99 - 017271

appliance when the mask or oral appliance does not extend into
the trachea or attach to an artificial airway;
(ii) Supplemental low flow oxygen therapy of less than six
(6) liters per minute, utilizing nasal cannula or continuous or
bilevel positive airway pressure during a polysomnogram;
(iii) Capnography during a polysomnogram;
(iv) Cardiopulmonary resuscitation;
(v) Pulse oximetry;
(vi) Gastroesophageal pH monitoring;
(vii) Esophageal pressure monitoring;
(viii) Sleep staging, including surface
electroencephalography, surface electrooculography, and surface
submental electromyography;
(ix) Surface electromyography;
(x) Electrocardiography;
(xi) Respiratory effort monitoring, including thoracic and
abdominal movement;
(xii) Plethysmography blood flow monitoring;
(xiii) Snore monitoring;
(xiv) Audio or video monitoring;
(xv) Body movement monitoring;
(xvi) Nocturnal penile tumescence monitoring;
(xvii) Nasal and oral airflow monitoring;
(xviii) Body temperature monitoring; and
(xiv) Monitoring the effects that a mask or oral appliance
used to treat sleep disorders has on sleep patterns; however, the
- 100 - 017271

mask or oral appliance must not extend into the trachea or attach
to an artificial airway;
(B) Observing and monitoring physical signs and symptoms,
general behavior, and general physical response to polysomnographic
evaluation and determining whether initiation, modification, or
discontinuation of a treatment regimen is warranted;
(C) Analyzing and scoring data collected during the monitoring
described in subdivisions (a)(7)(A) and (B) for the purpose of assisting a
licensed physician in the diagnosis and treatment of sleep and wake
disorders that result from developmental defects, the aging process,
physical injury, disease, or actual or anticipated somatic dysfunction;
(D) Implementation of a written or verbal order from a licensed
physician that requires the practice of polysomnography; and
(E) Education of a patient regarding the treatment regimen that
assists the patient in improving the patient's sleep; and
(8) "Sleep-related services" means acts performed by polysomnographic
technicians, polysomnographic trainees, polysomnographic students, and other
persons permitted to perform those services under this part, in a setting
described in subsection (c) that would be considered the practice of
polysomnography if performed by a polysomnographic technologist.
(b) A licensed dentist shall make or direct the making and use of any oral
appliance used to treat sleep disordered breathing and shall evaluate the structures of
the patient's oral and maxillofacial region for purposes of fitting the appliance.
(c) The practice of polysomnography must take place only in a hospital, a stand-
alone sleep laboratory or sleep center, or in the patient's home in accordance with a
physician's order; however, the scoring of data and the education of patients may take
place in settings other than in a sleep laboratory, sleep center, or the patient's home.
- 101 - 017271

63-33-802. Exemptions.
(a) This part does not limit or restrict a healthcare practitioner licensed under this
title from engaging in the full scope of practice of the person's profession.
(b) This part does not apply to diagnostic electroencephalograms conducted in
accordance with the guidelines of the American Clinical Neurophysiology Society.
63-33-803. Documentation required from applicants – License renewals.
(a) In addition to the requirements of § 63-33-103, an applicant for licensure
under this part shall provide documentation in the form required by the commissioner
that the applicant:
(1) Meets one (1) of the following educational requirements:
(A) Graduation from a polysomnographic educational program
that is accredited by the Commission on Accreditation of Allied Health
Education Programs;
(B) Graduation from a respiratory care educational program that
is accredited by the Commission on Accreditation of Allied Health
Education Programs and completion of the curriculum for a
polysomnography certificate established and accredited by the
Committee on Accreditation for Respiratory Care of the Commission on
Accreditation of Allied Health Education Programs;
(C) Graduation from an electro neurodiagnostic technologist
educational program with a polysomnographic technology track that is
accredited by the Commission on Accreditation of Allied Health Education
Programs; or
(D) Successful completion of an accredited sleep technologist
educational program (A-STEP) that is accredited by the American
Academy of Sleep Medicine;
- 102 - 017271

(2) Has passed the national certifying examination given by the Board of
Registered Polysomnographic Technologists;
(3) Is credentialed by the Board of Registered Polysomnographic
Technologists; and
(4) Has met any additional educational or clinical requirements
established by the commissioner.
(b) A person who was engaged in the practice of polysomnography on July 1,
2007, is eligible for licensure under this part without meeting the educational requirement
of subdivision (a)(1) if the person meets the requirements of subdivisions (a)(2)-(4).
(c) To be eligible for renewal of a license to engage in the practice of
polysomnography, a polysomnographic technologist must continue to be credentialed by
the Board of Registered Polysomnographic Technologists.
63-33-804. Unlicensed persons authorized to provide sleep-related services.
(a) The following persons may provide sleep-related services without being
licensed as a polysomnographic technologist under this part:
(1) A polysomnographic technician who provides sleep-related services
under the general supervision of a licensed physician for a period of up to one (1)
year from the date of the person's graduation from one (1) of the accredited
programs described in § 63-33-803(a)(1). The commissioner may, in the
commissioner's sole discretion, grant a one-time extension of up to three (3)
months beyond this one-year period;
(2) A polysomnographic trainee who provides sleep-related services
under the direct supervision of a polysomnographic technologist as a part of the
person's educational program while actively enrolled in an accredited sleep
technologist educational program (A-STEP) that is accredited by the American
Academy of Sleep Medicine;
- 103 - 017271

(3) A polysomnographic student who provides sleep-related services
under the direct supervision of a polysomnographic technologist as a part of the
person's educational program while actively enrolled in a polysomnographic
educational program that is accredited by the Commission on Accreditation of
Allied Health Education Programs (CAAHEP);
(4) A person who is credentialed in one (1) of the health-related fields
accepted by the Board of Registered Polysomnographic Technologists who
provides sleep-related services under the direct supervision of a
polysomnographic technologist, for a period of up to one (1) year, while obtaining
the clinical experience necessary to be eligible to sit for the examination given by
the Board of Registered Polysomnographic Technologists; and
(5) Respiratory therapists who provide polysomnography services after
being credentialed as a registered polysomnographic technologist by the Board
of Registered Polysomnographic Technologists, or as a sleep disorders specialist
by the National Board for Respiratory Care, or have undergone a standardized,
uniform mechanism to document competency in polysomnography as approved
by the commissioner. Documentation of such a credential or of passage of this
commissioner-approved mechanism must be made available at the request of
the commissioner. Respiratory therapists are not required to have a second
license as a polysomnographic technologist.
(b) Before providing sleep-related services, a polysomnographic technician shall
obtain a temporary permit from the commissioner. While providing sleep-related
services, the technician shall wear a badge that appropriately identifies the person as a
polysomnographic technician.
(c) Before providing sleep-related services, a polysomnographic trainee shall
give notice to the commissioner that the trainee is enrolled in an A-STEP educational
program accredited by the American Academy of Sleep Medicine. Trainees shall wear a
- 104 - 017271

badge that appropriately identifies the trainee as a polysomnographic trainee while
providing such services.
(d) Before providing sleep-related services, a person who is obtaining clinical
experience pursuant to subdivision (a)(4) shall give notice to the commissioner that the
person is working under the direct supervision of a polysomnographic technologist in
order to gain the experience to be eligible to sit for the examination given by the Board of
Registered Polysomnographic Technologists. The person shall wear a badge that
appropriately identifies the person while providing such services.
(e) Polysomnographic students must not receive compensation for sleep-related
services they provide and wear badges that appropriately identify them as students.
63-33-805. Use of title "Polysomnographic technologist."
A person who is licensed to engage in the practice of polysomnography in this
state has the right to use the title "polysomnographic technologist" or the abbreviation
"PSGP." Any other person shall not use that title or abbreviation, or any other words or
letters, indicating that the person is a polysomnographic technologist.
SECTION 43. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 33, is amended by adding
the following as a new part:
63-33-901. Part definitions – Authorized settings for the practice of respiratory
care – Exempted persons.
(a) As used in this part, unless the context otherwise requires:
(1) "Certified respiratory therapist" means a person licensed under this
part who has obtained and maintains the credential "certified respiratory
therapist" (CRT) or the credential "certified respiratory therapy technician"
(CRTT) from the National Board for Respiratory Care;
(2) "Practice of respiratory care":
(A)
(i) Means:
- 105 - 017271

(a) Under the supervision, control, and
responsibility of a licensed physician, the therapy,
management, education and instruction, rehabilitation,
diagnostic testing evaluation, and care of patients with
deficiencies and abnormalities that affect the
cardiorespiratory system and associated aspects of other
system functions; or
(b) Under the supervision, control, and
responsibility of a licensed physician, the performance of
cardiorespiratory research, cardiorespiratory health
promotion and disease prevention, and community
wellness and education programs;
(ii) Includes, under the supervision, control, and
responsibility of a licensed physician:
(a) The administration of pharmacologic agents
and medical gasses necessary to diagnose, implement
treatment, promote disease prevention, and provide
rehabilitation to the cardiorespiratory system; however, a
respiratory care practitioner shall not prescribe controlled
substances of any kind;
(b) The performance of specific diagnostic and
testing techniques employed in the medical management
of patients to assist in diagnosis, patient and family
education, monitoring, treatment, maintenance of patient
health status, and cardiorespiratory research, including,
but not limited to, pulmonary function testing,
- 106 - 017271

hemodynamic and physiologic monitoring and diagnosis of
cardiac function, and specimen collection and analysis;
(c) The establishment and maintenance of the
airways, bronchopulmonary hygiene, and cardiopulmonary
resuscitation, and cardiac and respiratory life support; and
(d) The receipt and implementation of written and
verbal physician orders and the development and
implementation of care plans and protocols;
(3) "Registered respiratory therapist" means a person licensed under this
part who has obtained and maintains the credential "registered respiratory
therapist" (RRT) from the National Board for Respiratory Care;
(4) "Respiratory assistant" or "assistant" means a person certified as
such pursuant to this part, who has:
(A) Received on-the-job training equivalent to at least one
thousand (1,000) hours of clinical training in respiratory care, during an
eighteen-consecutive-month period that was received under the
supervision of:
(i) A registered respiratory therapist;
(ii) A certified respiratory therapist; or
(iii) A licensed physician experienced in respiratory care;
and
(B) Passed a commissioner-approved examination for respiratory
assistants. The National Board for Respiratory Care (NBRC) entry level
examination, as provided to the board by the NBRC, by contract, is the
examination accepted by the commissioner. This examination does not
grant the respiratory assistant the NBRC credential. In addition, the
- 107 - 017271

commissioner may write the commissioner's own state board examination
or contract with other national testing organizations; and
(5) "Respiratory care practitioner" means a registered respiratory
therapist, a certified respiratory therapist, or a respiratory assistant licensed
under this part.
(b) The practice of respiratory care may be performed in an inpatient or
outpatient setting, clinic, hospital, nursing home facility, private dwelling, or other place
deemed appropriate or necessary.
(c) Registered respiratory therapists, certified respiratory therapists, and
respiratory assistants who have been issued a license or certificate by the
commissioner, pursuant to the authority of § 63-33-902, are exempt from any licensing,
certification, or permit requirements of the Tennessee Medical Laboratory Act, compiled
in title 68, chapter 29, for medical laboratory personnel or medical laboratory trainees
insofar as they engage in performing blood gases and PH analyses.
63-33-902. Licenses required – Documentation required from applicants – License
upgrades.
(a) In order to safeguard life, health, and property and promote public welfare by
requiring that only properly qualified persons practice respiratory care in this state, a
person practicing respiratory care must be licensed as provided in this part, and it is
unlawful for any person to practice or offer to practice respiratory care unless the person
has been duly licensed under this part, except as provided in this section.
(b)
(1) In addition to the requirements of § 63-33-103, an applicant for
licensure as a registered respiratory therapist shall provide documentation in the
form required by the commissioner that the applicant has successfully completed
a respiratory care educational program accredited by the Commission on
Accreditation of Allied Health Education Programs (CAAHEP) in collaboration
- 108 - 017271

with the Committee on Accreditation for Respiratory Care (CoARC), or their
successor organizations, and has successfully passed the National Board for
Respiratory Care registry examination for advanced respiratory therapists.
(2) In addition to the requirements of § 63-33-103, an applicant for
licensure as a certified respiratory therapist must provide documentation in the
form required by the commissioner that the applicant has successfully completed
a respiratory care educational program accredited by the CAAHEP in
collaboration with the CoARC, or their successor organizations, and has
successfully passed the National Board for Respiratory Care certification
examination for entry level respiratory therapists.
(3) After January 1, 2000, a person must not be licensed as a respiratory
assistant if that person has not been previously licensed as a respiratory
assistant in this state. However, persons who have been licensed as respiratory
assistants may continue to renew their licenses indefinitely so long as they meet
all the requirements for renewal.
(c)
(1) A person licensed to practice as a certified respiratory therapist may
upgrade the license to registered respiratory therapist if the person furnishes
evidence satisfactory to the commissioner that the person meets all the
requirements to be licensed as a registered respiratory therapist.
(2) A person licensed to practice as a respiratory assistant may upgrade
the license to certified respiratory therapist or registered respiratory therapist if
the person furnishes evidence satisfactory to the commissioner that the person
meets all the requirements to be licensed as a certified respiratory therapist or
registered respiratory therapist.
(3) A person must not hold more than one (1) license to practice
respiratory care in this state at the same time.
- 109 - 017271

63-33-903. Knowledge and skills required of registered respiratory therapists –
Independent clinical judgment authorized.
(a) The knowledge and skills for performing the functions of a registered
respiratory therapist must be acquired by academic and clinical preparation in a
respiratory care program approved by the Commission on Accreditation of Allied Health
Education Programs (CAAHEP), or its successor organization, or other accrediting
organization recognized by the commissioner or by registry from the National Board for
Respiratory Care. Registered respiratory therapists may assume primary clinical
responsibility for all respiratory care modalities. Such modalities must include, but are
not limited to, accepting telephone and verbal orders and responsibilities involving the
supervision of certified respiratory therapists and respiratory assistants.
(b) Under the supervision of a physician, a registered respiratory therapist may
be required to exercise considerable independent clinical judgment in the respiratory
care of patients. The registered respiratory therapist must also be capable of serving as
a technical resource person to the physician regarding current practices in respiratory
care and to the hospital staff regarding effective and safe methods for administering
respiratory care.
63-33-904. Knowledge and skills required of certified respiratory therapists –
Independent clinical judgment prohibited.
(a) The knowledge and skills for performing the functions of a certified
respiratory therapist must be acquired by academic and clinical preparation in a
respiratory care program approved by the Commission on Accreditation of Allied Health
Education Programs (CAAHEP), or its successor organization, or other accrediting
organization recognized by the commissioner or by certification from the National Board
for Respiratory Care. Under the supervision of a physician, certified respiratory
therapists may assume clinical responsibility for specified respiratory care modalities
involving the application of well-defined therapeutic techniques.
- 110 - 017271

(b) The certified respiratory therapist's role must not require the exercising of
independent clinical judgment; however, the certified respiratory therapist may be
expected to adjust or modify therapeutic techniques within well-defined procedures
based on a limited range of patient responses. The effective use of the certified
respiratory therapist, especially in the critical care setting, requires the supervision of a
physician experienced in respiratory care. The certified respiratory therapist may accept
telephone or verbal orders and responsibilities involving the supervision of respiratory
care therapists and respiratory assistants.
63-33-905. Knowledge and skills required of respiratory assistants – Independent
clinical judgment prohibited.
(a) The knowledge and skills for performing the functions of a respiratory
assistant must be acquired through compliance with the requirements of § 63-33-
901(a)(4).
(b) The assistant's role must not include the exercising of independent clinical
judgment. The assistant may be expected to adjust or modify therapeutic techniques
within well-defined procedures based on a limited range of patient responses. The use
of the assistant requires the supervision of a registered respiratory therapist, certified
respiratory therapist, or physician experienced in respiratory care. An assistant is not
permitted to perform the functions for which the assistant is certified on a critical care
patient being maintained on mechanical ventilation, unless the assistant possesses a
certificate that indicates the assistant has passed the critical care section of the board-
approved examination for respiratory assistants.
63-33-906. Exempted persons.
(a)
(1) This part does not prohibit:
- 111 - 017271

(A) A person licensed or certified to practice any of the other
health-related professions in this state under any other law from engaging
in the practice for which the person is licensed or certified; or
(B) Persons employed as subsidiary workers who do not
represent themselves to be registered respiratory therapists, certified
respiratory therapists, or respiratory assistants from assisting in the
respiratory care of patients under the direction and supervision of a
licensed physician.
(2) As used in this subsection (a), "subsidiary worker":
(A) Means an individual who occasionally administers oxygen or
other therapeutic gas under the orders of a licensed physician, osteopath,
or doctor of dentistry and who is not involved in any other aspect of the
direct delivery of respiratory care procedures or the administration of
diagnostic tests of the cardiorespiratory function; and
(B) Does not include an individual who delivers and installs
respiratory care equipment in hospitals, in the home, and in alternate care
sites.
(b) This part does not apply to a registered nurse or to a licensed practical nurse
employed by a licensed nursing home when such person is under the supervision of a
registered nurse or a licensed physician as long as such licensed practical nurse does
not maintain and manage life support systems.
(c) With respect to licensed healthcare professionals who lawfully engage in the
practice of respiratory care within the scope of practice of their professions, the
commissioner may develop mechanisms and standards for ensuring the competency of
such licensed professionals in their practice of respiratory care, and may recommend to
the health-related board for each such profession that that board adopt, by rule or
otherwise, mechanisms and standards for ensuring competency in the practice of
- 112 - 017271

respiratory care; however, the commissioner has no authority to regulate a healthcare
professional subject to rule by another health-related board.
(d) This part does not prohibit the practice of respiratory care by students while
they are under the supervision of instructors in a respiratory care educational program
that has been approved by the Commission on Accreditation of Allied Health Education
Programs (CAAHEP), or its successor organization, as long as the students' activities
are not performed for compensation and the students wear an appropriate badge
indicating their status as students.
(e) This part does not prohibit self-care by the patient or the gratuitous care by a
friend or member of the family who does not represent or hold out to be a respiratory
care practitioner licensed under this part.
(f) This part does not prohibit an individual who holds a credential from the
National Board for Respiratory Care entitled "certified pulmonary function technologist
(CPFT)" or "registered pulmonary function technologist (RPFT)" from engaging in the
performance of pulmonary function diagnostic testing.
63-33-907. Licensees authorized to perform blood gas analysis.
Blood gas analysis and maintenance and quality assurance of a blood gas
laboratory must not be performed by a practitioner licensed under this part unless:
(1) In the case of a registered respiratory therapist or certified respiratory
therapist, the registered respiratory therapist or certified respiratory therapist:
(A) Has been trained in blood gas analysis as approved by the
commissioner;
(B) Has been granted a license by the commissioner bearing the
endorsement "ABG analyst"; and
(C) Holds either the NBRC credentials "CRT," "CRTT," or "RRT"
or has passed a commissioner-approved examination testing competency
for blood gas analysis; and
- 113 - 017271

(2) In the case of a respiratory assistant:
(A) Has been trained in blood gas analysis as approved by the
commissioner;
(B) Has been granted a license by the commissioner bearing the
endorsement "ABG analyst"; and
(C) Has passed a commissioner-approved examination testing
competency for blood gas analysis. The National Board for Respiratory
Care entry level examination, as provided to the commissioner by the
NBRC by contract, is the examination accepted by the commissioner.
This examination does not grant the respiratory assistant the NBRC
credential. In addition, the commissioner may write the commissioner's
own state council examination or contract with other national testing
organizations.
63-33-908. Temporary license.
The commissioner may issue a temporary license to an individual applicant who
has completed the required respiratory care educational program but who has not yet
successfully completed the NBRC examination. A temporary license shall automatically
expire one (1) year from its date of issuance and must not be renewed.
63-33-909. Uniform standards for persons delivering and installing respiratory
equipment.
As a part of the board's licensing and regulation of home medical equipment
providers under § 68-11-226, the board for licensing health care facilities shall establish
uniform standards to ensure the competency of persons who deliver and install
respiratory equipment.
SECTION 44. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 63, Chapter 33, is amended by adding
the following as a new part:
63-33-1201. Part definitions.
- 114 - 017271

As used in this part:
(1) "Cosmetic medical service" means a service that uses a biologic or
synthetic material, a chemical application, a mechanical device, or a displaced
energy form of any kind that alters or damages, or is capable of altering or
damaging, living tissue to improve the patient's appearance or achieve an
enhanced aesthetic result;
(2) "Media" or "advertising":
(A) Means oral, written, and other types of communication
disseminated for the purpose of soliciting medical services; and
(B) Includes newspaper or magazine advertisements, telephone
directory displays, printed brochures or leaflets, websites, email
correspondence, and television or radio announcements;
(3) "Medical director" means a physician who:
(A) Holds an active medical license under chapter 6 or 9 of this
title in this state;
(B) Has an active medical practice in this state; and
(C) Is responsible for the provision of cosmetic medical services;
and
(4) "Medical spa":
(A) Means an entity, however named or organized, that offers or
performs cosmetic medical services; and
(B) Does not include an office or practice owned by a physician at
which the physician is physically present at least fifty percent (50%) of the
medical spa's regular hours of operation.
63-33-1202. Signage required.
- 115 - 017271

(a) An entity doing business as, or advertised as, a medical spa shall display the
name of the medical director and indicate one (1) of the following by signage at its
practice site and in its media and advertising:
(1) Whether the medical director is certified or eligible for certification by
a private or public board, parent association, multidisciplinary board, or
association that is a member of the American Board of Medical Specialties
(ABMS) or the American Osteopathic Association (AOA);
(2) Whether the medical director is certified by a board or association
with equivalent requirements to the ABMS or AOA as approved and recognized
by the board of medical examiners or the board of osteopathic examination, as
appropriate; or
(3) Whether the medical director is certified by a board or association
requiring an Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical Education (ACGME) or
AOA-approved training program that provides complete training in the specialty
or subspecialty certified, followed by prerequisite certification by a certifying
board of the ABMS or AOA in that training field and successful completion of an
additional examination in the specialty or subspecialty certified.
(b) If the medical director is not certified by any of the entities identified in
subsection (a), then the lack of certification must be displayed by signage at its practice
site and in its media and advertising.
63-33-1203. Regulation by board – Violations – Notice of changes in employment.
(a) Each licensed healthcare practitioner who provides services at a medical spa
must continue to be regulated only by the board that has issued a license to that
practitioner.
(b) A violation of this part, or a rule promulgated under this part, by a licensed
healthcare practitioner while providing services at a medical spa that is required be
- 116 - 017271

licensed by this part, is grounds for disciplinary action against that practitioner by the
board that licensed the practitioner.
(c) A licensed healthcare practitioner shall notify the board that has licensed the
practitioner within ten (10) days of starting or ending work at a medical spa.
63-33-1204. Rules.
In addition to the rulemaking authority conveyed to the commissioner in § 63-33-
102, the commissioner shall promulgate rules under this part that address the following
topics:
(1) Personnel requirements for the medical spa;
(2) Training requirements for healthcare providers;
(3) Patient records;
(4) Standards to ensure quality of patient care;
(5) Infection control;
(6) Health and safety requirements;
(7) Data collection and reporting requirements;
(8) Inspections; and
(9) Patient billing procedures.
63-33-1205. Documentation required from applicants.
(a) In addition to the requirements of § 63-33-103, an applicant for licensure
under this part shall provide the following documentation in the form required by the
commissioner:
(1) That the applicant for the medical spa license is the medical director
of the medical spa to be licensed;
(2) The medical license number of the medical director of the medical
spa and whether the medical director is a medical doctor or a doctor of
osteopathic medicine;
- 117 - 017271

(3) The certification information of the medical director as required by §
63-33-1202;
(4) A list of all medical spas in this state for which the applicant serves as
the medical director;
(5) A list of the names of all owners of the medical spa;
(6) A list of the names and Tennessee license numbers for employees
who will provide cosmetic medical service at the medical spa;
(7) The location of the medical spa; and
(8) Any other information the commissioner requires by rule.
(b) A medical spa license is only valid at the location identified in the licensure
application. Any changes in location require a new medical spa license, which must be
obtained via the initial licensure application process.
(c) A medical spa license is only valid while the original applicant serves as the
medical director of the medical spa. If a medical spa changes its medical director, then
a new medical spa license must be obtained via the initial licensure application process
by the new medical director.
(d) An existing licensed medical spa that changes medical directors may
continue to operate on the existing license for sixty (60) days after changing medical
directors so that there can be an orderly transition to the newly licensed medical spa.
63-33-1206. Information required from medical directors.
In addition to the updated information required by § 63-33-105(e), the medical
director of every licensed medical spa shall also provide the following information to the
division within thirty (30) days of their occurrence:
(1) The departure of a person identified in the application for licensure as
someone providing cosmetic medical services at the medical spa;
- 118 - 017271

(2) The name and Tennessee license number of a person not identified
in the original application form who will provide cosmetic services at the medical
spa;
(3) Any change in the ownership of the medical spa; and
(4) Any other information the commissioner requires by rule.
63-33-1207. Investigations by board.
Each board has the authority to investigate a complaint alleging a violation of this
part, or a rule adopted under this part, by a medical spa utilizing the services of a
healthcare practitioner licensed by that board. Each board also has the authority to
investigate a complaint alleging that a medical spa utilizing the services of a healthcare
practitioner licensed by that board is not properly licensed by the division as required by
this part.
63-33-1208. Investigations and discipline by commissioner.
The commissioner may investigate and discipline a medical spa license for
violations of this part or rules promulgated by the commissioner pursuant to this part, or
the reasons listed in § 63-33-106. The commissioner shall not investigate or discipline a
healthcare practitioner licensed by a board created under this title or under title 68.
SECTION 45. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 68-1-101(a)(8), is amended by
deleting the subdivision and substituting:
(8) The division of health related boards for all administrative, fiscal,
inspectional, and secretarial functions of the following boards, agencies, and
commissions:
(A) Board of alcohol and drug abuse counselors;
(B) Board for professional counselors, marital and family therapists, and
clinical pastoral therapists;
(C) Board of chiropractic examiners;
(D) Board of communication disorders and sciences;
- 119 - 017271

(E) Board of dentistry;
(F) Board of dietitian/nutritionist examiners;
(G) Board of examiners for nursing home administrators;
