SECTION 46. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 68-1-120, is amended by deleting
the section and substituting the following:
By December 31, 2026, and by each December 31 thereafter, the department of
health shall publish an annual report stating the total number of attempted suicides and
completed suicides that have occurred in this state using the most recent year of final
data available. The department of health shall submit the report electronically to all
members of the general assembly within seven (7) calendar days of the publication.
- 120 - 017271

SECTION 47. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 68-1-125(d), is amended by
deleting the subsection and substituting:
(d) The department of health, with ongoing consultation of appropriate experts
and representatives of relevant providers to provide such consultation, shall determine
which of its current programs are evidence-based, research-based, and theory-based.
The department of health shall make the measurements of the individual programs, as
set forth in subsection (c), available for review on its website.
SECTION 48. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 68-1-128(h)(4), is amended by
deleting the subdivision.
SECTION 49. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 68-1-128, is amended by adding
the following as a new subsection:
(j) The commissioner shall annually report to the chairs of the health and welfare
committee of the senate and the committee of the house of representatives having
jurisdiction over prescribers of controlled substances a summary of the data concerning
prescribers identified pursuant to this section, disciplinary actions taken against those
prescribers or taken related to prescription drug abuse or pain management clinics,
distribution and abuse of controlled substances, and access to the controlled substance
database.
SECTION 50. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 68-1-147(a)(4), is amended by
deleting the subdivision and substituting:
(4) "Palliative care" means specialized care focused on providing relief from
physical, psychological, and spiritual suffering, in order to maximize quality of life for
both the patient and family, that is provided for people facing a health condition that
carries a high risk of mortality, and:
(A) Negatively impacts a person's daily function;
(B) Negatively impacts a person's quality of life; or
(C) Excessively strains the person's caretaker.
- 121 - 017271

SECTION 51. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 68, Chapter 1, Part 1, is amended by
adding the following as a new section:
68-1-150. Rules.
(a) When legislation is enacted by the general assembly that requires a board
administratively attached to the department to promulgate rules in a prescribed period of
time, the board retains the exclusive authority to promulgate the rules until sixty (60)
days before the effective date of the legislation.
(b) If the board has not promulgated emergency rules and scheduled the
rulemaking hearing on permanent rules at least sixty (60) days before the effective date
of the legislation, the commissioner becomes the exclusive authority to promulgate the
rules as described in subsection (a). Upon the receipt of such authority, the
commissioner shall, in accordance with the Uniform Administrative Procedures Act,
compiled in title 4, chapter 5:
(1) Promulgate emergency rules, in accordance with § 4-5-208, within
the time required by the legislation; and
(2) Promulgate permanent rules within one hundred eighty (180) days of
the effective date of the emergency rules.
(c) Upon the completion of the requirements of subsection (b), the exclusive
authority to promulgate rules reverts to the board. The board may, at that time, amend
the permanent rules in accordance with the Uniform Administrative Procedures Act,
compiled in title 4, chapter 5.
(d) The rules promulgated by the commissioner in accordance with subsection
(b) remain in full force and effect, the same as if promulgated by the board, unless and
until the rules are amended by the board.
SECTION 52. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 68-1-2408, is amended by deleting
the section and substituting the following:
- 122 - 017271

(a) Entities receiving grants shall report to the health care and services facility as
often as the department determines to be beneficial to program oversight.
(b) The health care and services facility shall report to the department as often
as the department determines to be beneficial to program oversight, but at least
annually.
(c) The department shall publish annually a summary of program participation
and outcome measures.
SECTION 53. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 68-11-203, is amended by deleting
"fifteen (15)" in subdivision (b)(1) and substituting "sixteen (16)"; and by adding the following as
a new subdivision (b)(1)(C) and redesignating the existing subdivision (b)(1)(C) and subsequent
subdivisions accordingly:
(C) The commissioner of health, or an employee of the department of health,
designated by the commissioner;
SECTION 54. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 68-55-102(b), is amended by
deleting the subsection and substituting:
(b) The members are appointed to serve three-year or four-year terms. The
successor appointee for the half of the members with a service expiration closest in time
after July 1, 2026, shall serve three-year terms, while the other half of the members shall
serve four-year terms. Appointment of successors must match the three-year or four-
year term of the member they are appointed to succeed.
SECTION 55. The following rules are repealed on July 1, 2026:
(1) Tenn. Comp. R. & Regs. 0880-11;
(2) Tenn. Comp. R. & Regs. 0480-01;
(3) Tenn. Comp. R. & Regs. 0540-01, 0540-02, and 0540-03; and
(4) Tenn. Comp. R. & Regs. 1200-10-02.
SECTION 56.
- 123 - 017271

(a) The headings in this act are for reference purposes only and do not
constitute a part of the law enacted by this act. However, the Tennessee Code
Commission is requested to include the headings in any compilation or publication
containing this act.
(b) The use of "[former]" and "[repealed]" in this act are for notation purposes
only and do not constitute a part of the law enacted by this act. However, the
Tennessee Code Commission is requested to include such notations in any compilation
or publication containing this act.
(c) Except as provided in subsection (d), the Tennessee Code Commission is
requested to reserve parts 7, 10, and 11 in title 63, chapter 33.
(d) If House Bill 2145 / Senate Bill 2544 of the 114th general assembly becomes
a law, the Tennessee Code Commission is requested to redesignate the amendatory
language in Section 1 of House Bill 2145 / Senate Bill 2544 as new title 63, chapter 33,
part 10, and to revise references to such language in accordance with such
redesignation.
(e) If House Bill 658 / Senate Bill 502 of the 114th general assembly becomes a
law, the Tennessee Code Commission is requested to codify Sections 1, 2, 3, and 6 of
House Bill 658 / Senate Bill 502 in the following manner:
(1) The revisions in Section 1 of House Bill 658 / Senate Bill 502 should
be codified in § 63-33-301;
(2) The revisions in Section 2 of House Bill 658 / Senate Bill 502 should
be codified in § 63-33-302;
(3) The revisions in Section 3 of House Bill 658 / Senate Bill 502 should
be codified in § 63-33-303(2); and
(4) The revisions in Section 6 of House Bill 658 / Senate Bill 502 should
be codified as a new section in title 63, chapter 33, part 3.
SECTION 57. This act takes effect on July 1, 2026, the public welfare requiring it.
